{"title_page": "Jamaica national football team", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{About|the men's team|the women's team|Jamaica women's national football team}}\n{{Use Jamaican English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox national football team\n| Name                  = Jamaica\n| Badge                 = Flag of Jamaica.svg\n| Badge_size            = 150px\n| Nickname              = Reggae Boyz\n| Association           = [[Jamaica Football Federation]]\n| Sub-confederation     = [[Caribbean Football Union|CFU]] (Caribbean)\n| Confederation         = {{nowrap|[[CONCACAF]] (North America)}}\n| Coach                 = [[Theodore Whitmore]]\n| Captain               = [[Andre Blake]]\n| Most caps             = [[Ian Goodison]] (128)\n| Top scorer            = [[Luton Shelton]] (35)\n| Home Stadium          = [[Independence Park (Jamaica)|Independence Park]]\n| FIFA Trigramme        = JAM\n| FIFA Rank             = {{FIFA World Rankings|JAM}}\n| FIFA max              = 27\n| FIFA max date         = August 1998\n| FIFA min              = 116\n| FIFA min date         = October 2008\n| Elo Rank              = {{World Football Elo Ratings|Jamaica}}\n| Elo max               = 38\n| Elo max date          = 9 February 1998\n| Elo min               = 126\n| Elo min date          = 29 April 1984\n| pattern_b1            = _jam1819h\n| pattern_la1           = _jam1819h\n| pattern_ra1           = _jam1819h\n| pattern_sh1           = _jam1819h\n| pattern_so1           =\n| leftarm1              = FFDF00\n| body1                 = FFDF00\n| rightarm1             = FFDF00\n| shorts1               = 000000\n| socks1                = FFDF00 \n| pattern_b2            = _jam1819a\n| pattern_la2           = _jam1819a\n| pattern_ra2           = _jam1819a\n| pattern_sh2           = _jam1819a\n| pattern_so2           =\n| leftarm2              = 008040\n| body2                 = 008040\n| rightarm2             = 008040\n| shorts2               = FFDF00\n| socks2                = 000000\n| First game            = {{Fb|HAI|1859}} 1\u20132 {{fb-rt|JAM|1906}} <br> ([[Port-au-Prince]], [[Haiti]];<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesc/carib-tour2569.html |title=Caribbean Tour Matches 1925\u20131969 |editor=Courtney, Barrie |date=5 November 2014 |publisher=RSSSF |accessdate=24 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023131618/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesc/carib-tour2569.html |archive-date=23 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> 22 March 1925)\n| Largest win           = {{fb|JAM}} 12\u20130 {{fb-rt|VGB}} <br> ([[Grand Cayman]], [[Cayman Islands|Cayman Isls.]]; 4 March 1994) <br> {{fb|JAM}} 12\u20130 {{fb-rt|MAF}} <br> ([[Kingston, Jamaica]]; 24 November 2004)\n| Largest loss          = {{fb|CRC}} 9\u20130 {{fb-rt|JAM}} <br> ([[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|San Jos\u00e9]], [[Costa Rica]]; 24 February 1999)\n| World cup apps        = 1\n| World cup first       = 1998\n| World cup best        = Group stage ([[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998]])\n| Regional name         = [[CONCACAF Championship]] & [[CONCACAF Gold Cup|Gold Cup]]\n| Regional cup apps     = 13<!--as of 2019-->\n| Regional cup first    = [[1963 CONCACAF Championship|1963]]\n| Regional cup best     = Runners-up ([[2015 CONCACAF Gold Cup|2015]], [[2017 CONCACAF Gold Cup|2017]])\n| 2ndRegional name      = [[Copa Am\u00e9rica]]\n| 2ndRegional cup apps  = 2\n| 2ndRegional cup first = [[2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2015]]\n| 2ndRegional cup best  = Group stage ([[2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2015]], [[Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario|2016]])\n}}\n\nThe '''Jamaica national football team''', nicknamed the \"Reggae Boyz\", represents [[Jamaica]] in international [[association football|football]]. The team's first match was against [[Haiti national football team|Haiti]] in 1925. The squad is under the supervising body of the [[Jamaica Football Federation]] (JFF), which is a member of the [[Caribbean Football Union]] (CFU), [[CONCACAF|Confederation of North, Central American and Caribbean Association Football]] (CONCACAF), and the global jurisdiction of [[FIFA]]. Jamaica's home matches have been played at [[Independence Park (Jamaica)|Independence Park]] since its opening in 1962.\n\nThe national team has participated in three major football competitions. Their sole appearance in the [[FIFA World Cup]] was in [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998]], where the team finished third in its group and failed to advance. The team also competed in the [[Caribbean Cup]] winning six times. Jamaica also competes in the [[CONCACAF Gold Cup]], appearing thirteen times and finishing twice as runners-up to [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] in [[2015 CONCACAF Gold Cup|2015]] and the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] in [[2017 CONCACAF Gold Cup|2017]]. They also have been invited to the [[Copa Am\u00e9rica]] in 2015, and 2016 with both times being eliminated in the group stage.\n\n==History==\n\n=== Early history (1893\u20131962) ===\n[[File:19360113-thejamaicaxi.jpg|thumb|The Jamaica squad in 1936 taking on [[Trinidad and Tobago national football team|Trinidad and Tobago]]]]\nIn 1893, Jamaica's first football club, the [[Kingston Cricket Club]], was formed.<ref name=\"FascinationJamaica\" /> In 1910, the [[Jamaica Football Federation]] (JFF) was formed and controlled all of the games; in 1925, Jamaica was invited to play [[Haiti national football team|Haiti]] in a three match series with the team winning all three games 1\u20130, 2\u20131, and 3\u20130.<ref name=FascinationJamaica>{{cite web|url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/pages/history/story0077.html|title=A fascination with football|first=Rebecca|last=Tortello|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131103162120/http://jamaica-gleaner.com/pages/history/story0077.html|archive-date=3 November 2013|publisher=Jamaica Glenaer|access-date=29 May 2019}}</ref> In 1926, Jamaica hosted Haiti at [[Sabina Park]] and won 6\u20130.<ref name=\"FascinationJamaica\" /><ref name=JamaicaMatches>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesj/jam-intres.html|title=Jamaica \u2013 List of International Matches|date=6 March 2014|access-date=29 May 2019|first=Barrie|last=Courtney|publisher=RSSSF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110117042003/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesj/jam-intres.html|archive-date=17 January 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> At the [[Football at the 1930 Central American and Caribbean Games|1930 Central American Games]] in Cuba, Jamaica made its first international tournament appearance and lost both games in its group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesc/cag30.html|title=Central American Games 1930 (Cuba)|date=21 April 2011|access-date=29 May 2019|first=Erik|last=Garin|publisher=RSSSF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110182402/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesc/cag30.html|archive-date=10 November 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1925 to 1962, Jamaica had regular games with teams from [[Trinidad and Tobago national football team|Trinidad and Tobago]], Haiti, and [[Cuba national football team|Cuba]], as well as with clubs like the Haitian [[Racing CH]] and [[Violette AC]], the British [[Corinthian F.C.|Corinthians]], and the Argentinean [[Club Atl\u00e9tico Tigre|Tigers]].<ref name=\"FascinationJamaica\" /><ref name=JamaicaMatches/> In 1952, the Caribbean All-Star team was formed with players from Trinidad, Cuba, Haiti, and Suriname. The team played four matches against Jamaica in Sabina Park. Jamaica won the second game 2\u20131 and the fourth 1\u20130, and the All-Stars won the first game 5\u20131 and the third 1\u20130.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesj/jamcas52.html|title=Jamaica vs Caribbean All Stars 1952|last=Courtney|first=Barrie|date=8 August 2003|publisher=RSSSF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304080750/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesj/jamcas52.html|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=live|access-date=29 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Post-independence (1962\u20131989)===\nIn 1962, the same year Jamaica [[Independence of Jamaica|became independent]], the JFF became a member of FIFA.<ref name=\"FascinationJamaica\" /> At the [[Football at the 1962 Central American and Caribbean Games|1962 Central American and Caribbean Games]] played in Jamaica, the national team was led by Brazilian coach Jorge Penna.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20120215/news/news4.html|title=This day in 1962|date=15 February 2012|access-date=30 May 2019|publisher=[[Gleaner Company]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190530055228/http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20120215/news/news4.html|archive-date=30 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"JamaicaHistory\" /> Jamaica finished in fourth place, with two wins over [[Puerto Rico national football team|Puerto Rico]] and [[Cuba national football team|Cuba]].<ref name=1962CAC>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesc/cag62.html|title=Central American and Caribbean Games 1962 (Kingston, Jamaica)|date=16 January 2009|access-date=30 May 2019|first=Neil|last=Morrison|publisher=RSSSF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171219013901/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesc/cag62.html|archive-date=19 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> A year later, Jamaica competed in the first [[1963 CONCACAF Championship|CONCACAF Championship]] in El Salvador, where the team finished last in its group, which included [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]], the [[Netherlands Antilles national football team|Netherlands Antilles]], and eventual winner [[Costa Rica national football team|Costa Rica]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.concacaf.com/articles/20120406/costa-rica-wins-1963-norceca-title_2304746_2735454|title=Costa Rica wins 1963 NORCECA title|date=6 June 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120621061058/http://www.concacaf.com/articles/20120406/costa-rica-wins-1963-norceca-title_2304746_2735454|archive-date=21 June 2012|publisher=CONCACAF}}</ref>\n\nIn 1965, Jamaica attempted to qualify for the [[1966 FIFA World Cup]] in England. After finishing first in its preliminary group that included Cuba and the Netherlands Antilles, Jamaica faced Costa Rica and Mexico in the final round, where the winner would qualify for the World Cup. After a 3\u20132 loss at home in the opening match against Mexico, Jamaica lost the return match 8\u20130, with [[Isidoro D\u00edaz]] getting a [[hat-trick]] for Mexico. Jamaica then lost 7\u20130 to Costa Rica and ended with a draw at home in the return match, ultimately finishing with a single point.<ref name=JamaicaHistory>{{cite web|url=http://www.thereggaeboyz.com/history.htm|title=History of Jamaica's Football|access-date=30 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923065855/http://www.thereggaeboyz.com/history.htm|archive-date=23 September 2018|url-status=live|publisher=thereggaeboyz}}</ref> In January 1967, Jamaica attempted to qualify for the [[1967 CONCACAF Championship|CONCACAF Championship]] but was eliminated after finishing third in the group of five.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesc/conca67.html|title=III. CONCACAF Nations Cup 1967|date=8 May 2008|access-date=30 May 2019|first=Macario|last=Reyes|publisher=RSSSF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180816034759/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesc/conca67.html|archive-date=16 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 1968, George Hamilton became the new coach as Jamaica attempted to qualify for the [[1970 FIFA World Cup]] in Mexico.<ref name=\"JamaicaHistory\" /> Most of the squad for the campaign was young with only a few remaining players from its previous attempt at qualifying being in the team. This was due to most of its players being either retired or migrated abroad.<ref name=\"JamaicaHistory\" /> Jamaica finished last with zero points from four games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/70q.html|title=World Cup 1970 Qualifying|date=13 November 2006|access-date=31 May 2019|first=Karel|last=Stokkermans|publisher=RSSSF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181013001207/http://www.rsssf.com/tables/70q.html|archive-date=13 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=JamaicaHistory/> After finishing last in the [[1969 CONCACAF Championship]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesc/conca69.html|title=IV. CONCACAF Nations Cup 1969|date=13 November 2006|access-date=31 May 2019|first=Macario|last=Reyes|publisher=RSSSF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180918093056/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesc/conca69.html|archive-date=18 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and not qualifying for the [[1971 CONCACAF Championship qualification|following championship]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesc/conca71.html|title=V. CONCACAF Nations Cup 1971|date=3 January 2007|access-date=31 May 2019|first=Macario|last=Reyes|publisher=RSSSF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180816035254/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesc/conca71.html|archive-date=16 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Jamaica had to withdraw from qualifying for the [[1973 CONCACAF Championship]] after 17 players were suspended for poor behavior during a tour to Bermuda.<ref name=Jamaica>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/football-loftus-road-the-first-stop-for-jamaica-1151503.html|title=Football: Loftus Road the first stop for Jamaica|date=21 March 1998|access-date=2 June 2019|first=Nick|last=Harrias|publisher=The Independent|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303172144/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/football-loftus-road-the-first-stop-for-jamaica-1151503.html|archive-date=3 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1977, Jamaica competed in qualifying for the [[1977 CONCACAF Championship]], which was also the qualifier for the [[1978 FIFA World Cup]]. Taking on Cuba in the first round, Jamaica lost both of its games 5\u20131 on aggregate.<ref name=JamaicaHistory/>\n\nJamaica did not attempt to qualify for the [[1982 FIFA World Cup|1982]] and [[1986 FIFA World Cup|1986]] due to insufficient funds and a poorly prepared team.<ref name=\"JamaicaHistory\" /> The team returned to international competition after [[1989 CONCACAF Championship qualification|qualifying]] for the [[1989 CONCACAF Championship]], which was part of the qualifiers for the [[1990 FIFA World Cup]] in Italy. After defeating [[Puerto Rico national football team|Puerto Rico]] 3\u20131 on aggregate in the preliminary round, Jamaica played the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] for a spot in the finals. After a 0\u20130 draw at home, Jamaica lost 5\u20131 in the US and was eliminated.<ref name=JamaicaHistory/>\n\n===Caribbean triumph and World Cup appearance (1990\u20132000)===\nIn 1990, [[Carl Brown (footballer)|Carl Brown]] was signed as head coach and led Jamaica into qualifying for the [[1990 Caribbean Cup]], finishing tied for third place after the final round was abandoned due to Tropical Storm Arthur.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesc/caribe90.html|title=Caribbean Championship 1990|date=4 March 2011|access-date=5 June 2019|first=Barrie|last=Courtney|publisher=RSSSF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180816035249/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesc/caribe90.html|archive-date=16 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1991, Jamaica defeated Trinidad and Tobago 2\u20130 to win the [[1991 Caribbean Cup|Caribbean Cup]] and qualify for the [[1991 CONCACAF Gold Cup|CONCACAF Gold Cup]].<ref>{{cite article|url=http://www.ttfootballhistory.com/node/1456|title=Jamaica conquer Trinidad|date=3 June 1991|page=11|first=H.G|last=Helps|publisher=Jamaica Gleaner|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20151206061738/http://www.ttfootballhistory.com/node/1456|archive-date=6 December 2015|access-date=5 June 2019}}</ref> In the Gold Cup, Jamaica finished last with zero points in a group consisting of [[Honduras national football team|Honduras]], Mexico, and [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/91gc.html|title=CONCACAF Championship, Gold Cup 1991|date=9 July 2001|access-date=5 June 2019|first=Fran\u00e7ois|last=Mazet|publisher=RSSSF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304205944/http://www.rsssf.com/tables/91gc.html|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter the Jamaicans lost to Trinidad and Tobago in the final of the [[1992 Caribbean Cup]],<ref>{{cite article|url=https://ttfootballhistory.comnode/1441|title=Trinidad regain Shell Cup|date=27 June 1992|page=13|publisher=Jamaica Gleaner|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20151206061748/http://www.ttfootballhistory.com/node/1441|archive-date=6 December 2015|access-date=6 June 2019}}</ref> they started their campaign in preliminary rounds of [[1994 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONCACAF)|qualifying]] for the [[1994 FIFA World Cup|1994 World Cup]]. After defeating Puerto Rico 3\u20131 on aggregate in the second preliminary round, Jamaica eliminated Trinidad and Tobago and  was grouped with [[Bermuda national football team|Bermuda]], [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada]], and [[El Salvador national football team|El Salvador]], two of which would advance to the final round. Jamaica opened the second round with two 1\u20131 draws against Canada and Bermuda, but the team lost its return match in Canada after a single goal from [[Dale Mitchell (soccer)|Dale Mitchell]]. After a 3\u20132 home win over Bermuda and two losses to El Salvador, Jamaica finished in third place and was eliminated.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jff.live/about/|title=About the JFF|access-date=6 June 2019|publisher=Jamaican Football Federation|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190525104402/https://www.jff.live/about/|archive-date=25 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, Jamaica finished in second place after losing on penalties to [[Martinique national football team|Martinique]] in the final of the [[1993 Caribbean Cup|Caribbean Cup]], which was a qualifier for the [[1993 CONCACAF Gold Cup|CONCACAF Gold Cup]] which was held later that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesg/gold-car93.html|title=Shell Caribbean Cup 1993|date=18 July 2002|access-date=6 June 2019|first=Chris|last=McKain|publisher=RSSSF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130107014521/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesg/gold-car93.html|archive-date=7 January 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> During this tournament, the team opened with a 1\u20130 loss to the US before recording their first Gold Cup win against Honduras. After qualifying in second place with a 1\u20131 draw against Honduras, Jamaica lost 6\u20131 to Mexico in the semi-final in Mexico City.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/93gc.html|title=CONCACAF Championship, Gold Cup 1993|date=18 July 2002|access-date=6 June 2019|first=Fran\u00e7ois|last=Mazet|publisher=RSSSF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023115934/http://www.rsssf.com/tables/93gc.html|archive-date=23 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> After not qualifying for the final round of the [[1994 Caribbean Cup]] despite recording its largest-ever win margin in a 12\u20130 win against the [[British Virgin Islands national football team|British Virgin Islands]], the team decided to hire [[Ren\u00e9 Sim\u00f5es]] to assist Brown with the goal of qualifying for the [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998 World Cup]].<ref name=FascinationJamaica/> After being eliminated in the group stage of both the [[1995 Caribbean Cup]] by virtue of head-to-head and the [[1996 Caribbean Cup]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesg/gold-car95.html|title=Shell Caribbean Cup 1995|date=12 September 2003|first=Chris|last=McKain|publisher=RSSSF|access-date=11 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180816033000/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesg/gold-car95.html|archive-date=16 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tabless/shell-car96.html|title=Shell Caribbean Cup 1996|date=24 July 2003|first=Chris|last=McKain|publisher=RSSSF|access-date=11 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180816033324/http://www.rsssf.com/tabless/shell-car96.html|archive-date=16 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Jamaica opened its 1998 World Cup qualifiers with an 2\u20130 aggregate win over [[Suriname national football team|Suriname]] and defeated [[Barbados national football team|Barbados]] 3\u20130 in the following round.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition=1013/preliminaries/preliminary=892/index.html|title=1998 FIFA World Cup France \u2122 Preliminaries|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231124323/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition=1013/preliminaries/preliminary=892/index.html|archive-date=31 December 2013|publisher=FIFA|access-date=11 June 2019}}</ref> In 1997, Sim\u00f5es scouted for players in England that had Jamaican heritage to join the national team. [[Paul Hall (footballer)|Paul Hall]], [[Fitzroy Simpson]], [[Deon Burton]] and [[Robbie Earle]] were all named in the squad due their heritage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ipsnews.net/1998/04/sport-jamaica-burst-of-nationalism-hits-football-squad/|title=SPORT-JAMAICA: Burst of Nationalism Hits Football Squad|date=21 April 1998|access-date=11 June 2019|location=Kingston|first=Howard|last=Campbell|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422084518/http://www.ipsnews.net/1998/04/sport-jamaica-burst-of-nationalism-hits-football-squad/|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> After finishing winless in the first four games of the final qualifying round, Jamaica recorded three 1\u20130 wins over El Salvador, Canada, and Costa Rica, with Burton scoring the winning goal in each of the latter two matches. After a 0\u20130 draw against Mexico, Jamaica secured its qualification and made its first-ever World Cup appearance, and the following day was declared a national holiday.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/world-cup/world-cup-2018-jamaica-france-98-robbie-earle-media-makers-history-maker-reggae-boyz-a8400226.html|title=World Cup 2018: How history-making Jamaica became more than just the \u2018Reggae Boyz\u2019 at France 1998|date=15 June 2018|access-date=13 June 2019|first=Eoin|last=O'Callaghan|publisher=The Independent|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615163216/https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/world-cup/world-cup-2018-jamaica-france-98-robbie-earle-media-makers-history-maker-reggae-boyz-a8400226.html|archive-date=15 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, Jamaica competed at the [[1998 CONCACAF Gold Cup]], finishing first in a group comprising World Cup champion [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]], Guatemala, and El Salvador. With the help of goalkeeper [[Warren Barrett]], Jamaica opened with a 0\u20130 tie against Brazil.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1998-feb-04-sp-15402-story.html|title=Brazil Can Do No Better Than 0\u20130 Tie With Jamaica|date=4 February 1998|access-date=13 June 2019|publisher=LA Times|location=Miami}}</ref> After wins over Guatemala and El Salvador, Jamaica advanced to the semi-final against Mexico. The match went into overtime before Mexican player [[Luis Hernandez (footballer)|Luis Hernandez]] scored the winning goal. In the third-place playoff, Jamaica lost 1\u20130 to Brazil, ending in fourth place.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insideworldfootball.com/1998-gold-cup/|title=Gold Cup 1998|date=13 June 2019|access-date=13 June 2019}}</ref> At the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]], Jamaica finished third in Group H with three points from a 2\u20131 win against [[Japan national football team|Japan]] in Lyon. [[Theodore Whitmore]] scored both goals in the victory.<ref name=JapanvsJamaica1998>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefreelibrary.com/Reggae+Boyz+end+their+adventure+with+a+victory%3b+JAPAN+1+JAMAICA+2.-a060783367|title=Reggae Boyz end their adventure with a victory; Japan 1 Jamaica 2.|date=27 June 1998|access-date=13 June 2019|publisher=Birmingham Post}}</ref>\n\nThe following month, Jamaica competed in the finals of the [[1998 Caribbean Cup]], which was a qualifier for the [[2000 CONCACAF Gold Cup]]. After finishing first in its group, Jamaica won the final 2\u20131 against Trinidad and Tobago, with goals from Oneil McDonald and [[Dean Sewell]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rsssf.com/tabless/shell-car98.html|title=Shell Caribbean Cup 1998|first=Barrie|last=Courtney|date=26 November 2010|access-date=17 June 2019|publisher=RSSSF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709193353/http://www.rsssf.com/tabless/shell-car98.html|archive-date=9 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1999, Jamaica experienced its biggest defeat in a 9\u20130 loss against Costa Rica.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thereggaeboyz.com/news12.htm#FEBRUARY|title=Costa Rica Trash Jamaica 9\u20130|date=27 February 1999|access-date=17 June 2019|publisher=thereggaeboyz|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303235818/http://www.thereggaeboyz.com/news12.htm#FEBRUARY|archive-date=3 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> After finishing second in its group, Jamaica was eliminated by Cuba in the semi finals of the [[1999 Caribbean Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rsssf.com/tablesc/caribe99.html|title=Copa Caribe 1999|first=James|last=Goloboy|date=7 October 1999|access-date=17 June 2019|publisher=RSSSF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920001452/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesc/caribe99.html|archive-date=20 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> At the Gold Cup, Jamaica finished last in its group, losing against [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]] and Honduras 2\u20130 and 1\u20130, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wvw.nacion.com/ln_ee/futbol/copaoro2000/noticiascafe.html|title=Peru debuts with a draw, Honduras and Colombia advance in the Gold Cup|location=Miami|date=15 February 2000|access-date=17 June 2019|publisher=Nacion|language=es|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190617021158/http://wvw.nacion.com/ln_ee/futbol/copaoro2000/noticiascafe.html|archive-date=17 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Struggles at continental level (2001\u20132009)===\nIn the [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONCACAF)|2002 FIFA World Cup qualification]] semi-finals, Jamaica faced Honduras, El Salvador, and [[Saint Vincent and the Grenadines national football team|Saint Vincent and the Grenadines]] in the second group. Jamaica finished second, securing a spot in the final round despite losing two games to Honduras and El Salvador. In the final round of qualifying, Jamaica finished in fifth place after being eliminating by Honduras.<ref name=2002WCQ>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/2002q.html|title=World Cup 2002 Qualifying|first=Karel|last=Stokkermans|date=13 September 2018|access-date=17 June 2019|publisher=RSSSF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090116173331/http://www.rsssf.com/tables/2002q.html|archive-date=16 January 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> Between the two rounds of World Cup qualifying, Jamaica was eliminated in the group stage of the [[2001 Caribbean Cup]] by goal-difference and missed out on qualifying for the [[2002 CONCACAF Gold Cup|Gold Cup]] the following year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rsssf.com/tablesc/caribe01.html|title=Copa Caribe 2001|first=Chris|last=McKain|date=21 August 2004|access-date=17 June 2019|publisher=RSSSF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181008125312/http://rsssf.com/tablesc/caribe01.html|archive-date=8 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Jamaica qualified for the [[2003 CONCACAF Gold Cup|2003 Gold Cup]], reaching the quarter-finals before being eliminated by Mexico 5\u20130 at the [[Estadio Azteca]].<ref>{{cite web|title=CONCACAF 2003 Gold Cup technical report|url=http://www.concacaf.com/staticFiles/b6/43/0,,12813~148406,00.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130407191543/http://www.concacaf.com/staticFiles/b6/43/0,,12813~148406,00.pdf|archive-date=7 April 2013|publisher=CONCACAF}}</ref>\n\nJamaica started its [[2006 FIFA World Cup]] qualifying campaign in the [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 CONCACAF Second Round|second round]] with a 4\u20131 aggregate win over Haiti to reach the [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 CONCACAF Third Round|third round]]. Jamaica finished third in group play, with a 1\u20131 draw against the US and one point away from reaching the next round. Coach [[Sebasti\u00e3o Lazaroni]] was sacked due to the team's performance.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lazaroni says sorry|date=19 November 2004|url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20041119/sports/sports1.html|first=Audley|last=Boyd|publisher=Jamaica Gleaner|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041204035601/http://www.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20041119/sports/sports1.html|archive-date=4 December 2004|access-date=17 June 2019}}</ref> In the [[2005 Caribbean Cup]], Jamaica tied its largest-ever win margin record with a 12\u20130 win over [[Saint Martin national football team|Saint Martin]], with [[Luton Shelton]] and Roland Dean both getting hat-tricks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20041126/sports/sports4.html|title=Goals galore in store for fans|date=26 November 2004|first=Audley|last=Boyd|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041214074756/http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20041126/sports/sports4.html|archive-date=14 December 2004|publisher=Jamaica Gleaner}}</ref> After reaching the final with wins against Saint Lucia and [[French Guiana national football team|French Guiana]], Jamaica claimed its third title and a spot at the Gold Cup.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20050225/sports/sports1.html|title=Boyz clinch Carib crown|date=15 February 2005|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070612191635/http://www.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20050225/sports/sports1.html|archive-date=12 June 2007|publisher=Jamaica Gleaner}}</ref> At the [[2005 CONCACAF Gold Cup|Gold Cup]], Jamaica reached the quarter finals before losing to the US 3\u20131 in [[Foxborough, Massachusetts|Foxborough]], with American player [[DaMarcus Beasley]] scoring two goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.us.terra.com/goldcup2005/us/interna/0,,OI594252-EI4900,00.html|title=Beasley leads United States over Jamaica 3\u20131|date=16 July 2005|publisher=Gold Cup|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060701063600/http://www.us.terra.com/goldcup2005/us/interna/0,,OI594252-EI4900,00.html|archive-date=1 July 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006 and 2007, Jamaica continued to struggle, with one Jamaican journalist dubbing the team \"The Reggae Toyz\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20060604/sports/sports9.html|title=Final word \u2013 How did the Boyz become Toyz?|date=4 June 2006|first=Tym|last=Glaser|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071009041535/http://www.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20060604/sports/sports9.html|archive-date=9 October 2007|publisher=Jamaica Gleaner}}</ref> The team failed to qualify for the [[2007 Caribbean Cup]] after being eliminated due to goals scored, with St. Vincent and the Grenadines scoring three more goals than Jamaica.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20061002/sports/sports1.html|title=Reggae Boyz crash out \u2013 Defending champs fail to advance in Digicel Caribbean Cup despite 2\u20130 win|date=2 October 2006|first=Howard|last=Walker|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061106171448/http://www.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20061002/sports/sports1.html|archive-date=6 November 2006|publisher=Jamaica Gleaner|access-date=18 June 2019}}</ref> Two managers later, the team only earned a single point from three matches in the third round of [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 CONCACAF Third Round#Group 2|qualification]] for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]]. With coach [[Theodore Whitmore]], Jamaica secured three wins from its remaining matches, jumping from 116th{{efn-ua|Which at the time was their lowest ranking}} to 83rd place in the world rankings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/fifa-world-ranking/news/resurgent-jamaica-dream-946115|title=Resurgent Jamaica dream on|date=13 November 2008|access-date=21 June 2019|publisher=FIFA|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621014136/https://www.fifa.com/fifa-world-ranking/news/resurgent-jamaica-dream-946115|archive-date=21 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Despite the team's final win over [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada]], Jamaica was eliminated by goal difference after Mexico finished three goals ahead.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/va33g8lvjew7h8lcmdwm.pdf?cloudid=va33g8lvjew7h8lcmdwm|title=2010 FIFA World Cup South Africa\u2122 Technical Report and Statistics|page=208|publisher=FIFA}}</ref> Jamaica won the [[2008 Caribbean Cup]], with [[Luton Shelton]] scoring both goals in the victory against [[Grenada national football team|Grenada]] to qualify for the [[2009 CONCACAF Gold Cup|Gold Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20081215/sports/sports1.html|title=Jamaica's Reggae Boyz rule the Caribbean|first=Audley|last=Boyd|date=15 December 2008|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090323032651/http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20081215/sports/sports1.html|archive-date=23 March 2009|publisher=Jamaica Gleaner}}</ref> At the Gold Cup, Jamaica finished third in its group; with a single win over El Salvador, the side finished last among the third-place teams and was eliminated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/09gc.html|title=CONCACAF Championship, Gold Cup 2009|first=Erik|last=Francisco Lugo|date=25 March 2011|access-date=21 June 2019|publisher=RSSSF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004024107/http://www.rsssf.com/tables/09gc.html|archive-date=4 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Continental finals appearances (2010\u20132019)===\n[[File:Usa v jamaica, Gold Cup 2011.jpg|thumb|Jamaica taking on the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] at the [[2011 CONCACAF Gold Cup]]]]\nJamaica entered the final round of the [[2010 Caribbean Cup]] after a 0\u20130 draw with [[Costa Rica national football team|Costa Rica]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://au.soccerway.com/matches/2010/11/18/world/friendlies/jamaica/costa-rica/1047848/|title=Jamaica vs. Costa Rica \u2013 18 November|access-date=21 June 2019|website=soccerway|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131122132009/http://au.soccerway.com/matches/2010/11/18/world/friendlies/jamaica/costa-rica/1047848/|archive-date=22 November 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> After finishing first in its group, Jamaica won against Grenada in the semi-finals, then defeating first-time finalists [[Guadeloupe national football team|Guadeloupe]] in a penalty shoot-out. Jamaica earned its fifth title, and coach [[Theodore Whitmore]] became the first to win the [[Caribbean Cup]] as both player and coach.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dcc.digicelfootball.com/news/89-dcc-semi-final-match-53-jamaica-2-vs-grenada-1-aet|title=Reggae Boyz advance but get their toughest test yet|date=3 December 2010|location=[[Stade Pierre-Aliker]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120514112738/http://dcc.digicelfootball.com/news/89-dcc-semi-final-match-53-jamaica-2-vs-grenada-1-aet|archive-date=14 May 2012|publisher=Digicel Football\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20101206/sports/sports1.html|title=Well Done Reggae Boyz!|first=Audley|last=Boyd|date=6 December 2010|access-date=21 June 2019|location=[[Stade Pierre-Aliker]]|publisher=Jamaica Gleaner|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621022846/http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20101206/sports/sports1.html|archive-date=21 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In the [[2011 CONCACAF Gold Cup]], Jamaica finished first in its group, beating Grenada 4\u20130, Guatemala 2\u20130, and Honduras 1\u20130 before being eliminated by the US, with goals from American players [[Jermaine Jones]] and [[Clint Dempsey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goldcup.org/page/GoldCup/NewsDetail/0,,12802~2378694,00.html|title=CONCACAF Gold Cup Lookahead: Sunday Quarterfinals|date=19 June 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110809083527/http://www.goldcup.org/page/GoldCup/NewsDetail/0,,12802~2378694,00.html|archive-date=9 August 2011|publisher=CONCACAF}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goldcup.org/page/GoldCup/NewsDetail/0,,12802~2378704,00.html|title=Jones, Dempsey put U.S. past Jamaica, into semis|date=19 June 2011|location=[[Washington, D.C.]]|publisher=CONCACAF|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110808052710/http://www.goldcup.org/page/GoldCup/NewsDetail/0,,12802~2378704,00.html|archive-date=8 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONCACAF)|qualifying]] for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]], Jamaica started in the third round and earned seven points in the first three games, which included a historic 2\u20131 win over the United States at home which was their first win over the Americans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20120908/sports/sports1.html|title=Brilliant Boyz|first=Audley|last=Boyd|date=8 September 2012|access-date=25 June 2019|publisher=Jamaica Gleaner|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828102201/http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20120908/sports/sports1.html|archive-date=28 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Jamaica later qualified with a 4\u20131 win over Antigua and Barbuda, finishing two goals ahead of Guatemala in its group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20121017/sports/sports1.html|title=Brilliant Boyz Advance|first=Audley|last=Boyd|date=17 October 2012|access-date=25 June 2019|publisher=Jamaica Gleaner|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224234054/http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20121017/sports/sports1.html|archive-date=24 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> After the team finished last in its group for the [[2012 Caribbean Cup]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20121213/sports/sports2.html|title=Boyz Out!|date=13 December 2012|access-date=25 June 2019|publisher=Jamaica Gleaner|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828131737/http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20121213/sports/sports2.html|archive-date=28 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and failed to record a win in six matches in the [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 CONCACAF Fourth Round|fourth round]] of qualifying, team manager Theodore Whitmore resigned and was replaced by German coach [[Winfried Sch\u00e4fer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20130613/sports/sports1.html|title=Whitmore Had To Go \u2013 Burrell|first=Ryon|last=Jones|date=13 June 2013|access-date=25 June 2019|publisher=Jamaica Gleaner|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004042646/http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20130613/sports/sports1.html|archive-date=4 October 2018|url-status=live}} After a 2\u20130 loss to the US, Jamaica finished in last place and was eliminated.\n\nAfter qualifying for the [[2015 CONCACAF Gold Cup|2015 Gold Cup]] due to winning the [[2014 Caribbean Cup]],<ref name=2014CC>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/2014/11/18/jamaica-capture-caribbean-cup-shootout-win-over-trinidad-tobago-unions-andre|title=Jamaica capture Caribbean Cup in shootout win over Trinidad & Tobago; Union's Andre Blake makes key save|date=18 November 2014|publisher=MLS|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141222145740/https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/2014/11/18/jamaica-capture-caribbean-cup-shootout-win-over-trinidad-tobago-unions-andre|archive-date=22 December 2014}}</ref> Jamaica was invited to compete in the [[2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2015 edition]] of the [[Copa Am\u00e9rica]] in Chile.<ref name=CopaInvite>{{cite web|title=Jamaica to tackle Copa America|url=http://rjrnewsonline.com/sports/jamaica-to-tackle-copa-america|publisher=rjrnewsonline|accessdate=25 June 2019|date=24 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813111525/http://rjrnewsonline.com/sports/jamaica-to-tackle-copa-america|archive-date=13 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> At the Copa America, Jamaica was drawn in [[2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica Group B|Group B]] with [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]], [[Paraguay national football team|Paraguay]], and [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]]. Jamaica finished last after losing all three of its matches 1\u20130, with [[Jobi McAnuff]] saying, \"I don\u2019t think many people would have given us that chance.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/sport/Boyz-look-ahead|title=Copa America big boost as Jamaica look to Gold Cup, World Cup qualifiers|date=23 June 2015|location=[[Vi\u00f1a del Mar]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423194332/http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/sport/Boyz-look-ahead|archive-date=23 April 2016|publisher=Jamaica Observer}}</ref> A few weeks later in the [[2015 CONCACAF Gold Cup|2015 Gold Cup]], Jamaica finished first in its group and defeated Haiti in the quarter-finals with a goal from [[Giles Barnes]] to qualify for the semi-finals for the first time since 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/soccer/2015/07/18/jamaica-beats-haiti-1-0--play-us--gold-cup-semifinal/30367917/|title=Jamaica beats Haiti, will play U.S. in Gold Cup semifinal|location=[[Baltimore]]|date=19 July 2015|access-date=26 June 2019|publisher=USA Today|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721221745/http://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/soccer/2015/07/18/jamaica-beats-haiti-1-0--play-us--gold-cup-semifinal/30367917/|archive-date=21 July 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In the semi-final, Jamaica defeated the US 2\u20131 with goals from [[Darren Mattocks]] and Giles Barnes, reaching its first-ever Gold Cup final. In the final, Jamaica lost to [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] 3\u20131.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2015/07/22/usa-1-jamaica-2-concacaf-gold-cup-match-recap|title=USA 1, Jamaica 2 \u2013 CONCACAF Gold Cup Match Recap|first=Andrew|last=Wiebe|location=[[Atlanta]]|date=22 July 2015|access-date=26 June 2019|publisher=MLS|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211210013/http://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2015/07/22/usa-1-jamaica-2-concacaf-gold-cup-match-recap|archive-date=11 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/planet-futbol/2015/07/26/mexico-jamaica-concacaf-gold-cup-final-andres-guardado-usa-confederations-playoff|title=Mexico beats Jamaica to win seventh Gold Cup, set up meeting with USA|location=[[Philadelphia]]|first=Brian|last=Straus|date=26 July 2015|access-date=26 June 2019|publisher=SI|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626004526/https://www.si.com/planet-futbol/2015/07/26/mexico-jamaica-concacaf-gold-cup-final-andres-guardado-usa-confederations-playoff|archive-date=26 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONCACAF)|qualifying]] for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]], Jamaica started in the [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 CONCACAF Third Round|third round]] and defeated Nicaragua 4\u20133 on aggregate to reach the fourth round.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/article/sports/20150908/full-time-jamaica-beat-nicaragua-2-0-advance-semis-world-cup-qualifiers|title=FULL TIME: Jamaica Beat Nicaragua 2\u20130 To Advance To Semis Of World Cup Qualifiers|date=8 September 2015|access-date=26 June 2019|publisher=Jamaica Gleaner|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151025165035/http://jamaica-gleaner.com/article/sports/20150908/full-time-jamaica-beat-nicaragua-2-0-advance-semis-world-cup-qualifiers|archive-date=25 October 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In the [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 CONCACAF Fourth Round#Group B|fourth round]], Jamaica started off strong with a 1\u20130 win over Haiti and a 1\u20131 draw with Costa Rica, earning four points after three games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/article/sports/20160326/disappointing-draw-reggae-boyz-costa-rica-hold-jamaica-1-1-result|title=Disappointing Draw For Reggae Boyz ... Costa Rica Hold Jamaica To 1\u20131 Result|date=26 March 2016|access-date=26 June 2019|publisher=Jamaica Gleaner|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328054935/http://jamaica-gleaner.com/article/sports/20160326/disappointing-draw-reggae-boyz-costa-rica-hold-jamaica-1-1-result|archive-date=28 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> However, three straight losses, including a 2\u20130 loss against Panama, eliminated Jamaica from World Cup qualifying.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/article/sports/20160902/jas-cup-hopes-end-after-2-0-defeat|title=Ja's Cup Hopes End After 2\u20130 Defeat|date=2 September 2016|access-date=26 June 2019|publisher=Jamaica Gleaner|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161110112445/http://jamaica-gleaner.com/article/sports/20160902/jas-cup-hopes-end-after-2-0-defeat|archive-date=10 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Between the fourth-round matches, Jamaican competed in the [[Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario]] after qualifying through the [[2014 Caribbean Cup]]. Jamaica finished with no points from their three games, scoring no goals and conceding six.<ref name=2014CC/><ref name=JAMvURU2016>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/soccer/2016/06/14/uruguay-snaps-five-game-copa-america-winless-streak/85856152/|title=Uruguay snaps five-game Copa America winless streak with victory over Jamaica|location=[[Santa Clara, California|Santa Clara]]|date=14 June 2016|access-date=26 June 2019|publisher=USA Today|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160614214930/http://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/soccer/2016/06/14/uruguay-snaps-five-game-copa-america-winless-streak/85856152/|archive-date=14 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter Whitmore returned to the team,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/article/sports/20160927/whitmores-boyz-jerome-waite-hired-assistant-coach-jff-responds-brown|title=Whitmore's Boyz \u2013 Jerome Waite Hired As Assistant Coach, As JFF Responds To Brown|first=Dania|last=Bogle|date=27 September 2016|access-date=26 June 2019|publisher=Jamaica Gleaner|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160929201704/http://jamaica-gleaner.com/article/sports/20160927/whitmores-boyz-jerome-waite-hired-assistant-coach-jff-responds-brown|archive-date=29 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Jamaica qualified for the [[2017 Caribbean Cup]], reaching the final before losing to first-time finalists [[Cura\u00e7ao national football team|Cura\u00e7ao]] 2\u20131, with [[Elson Hooi]] scoring both of Cura\u00e7ao's goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/article/sports/20170625/curacao-shock-jamaica-lift-caribbean-cup|title=Curacao Shock Jamaica To Lift Caribbean Cup|first=Marc|last=Stamp|date=25 June 2017|access-date=26 June 2019|publisher=Jamaica Gleaner|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919203252/http://jamaica-gleaner.com/article/sports/20170625/curacao-shock-jamaica-lift-caribbean-cup|archive-date=19 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In the [[2017 CONCACAF Gold Cup|2017 Gold Cup]], Jamaica upset Mexico 1\u20130 in the semi-finals, with [[Kemar Lawrence]] scoring the goal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/soccer/ct-jamaica-mexico-concacaf-gold-cup-20170723-story.html|title=Jamaica stuns Mexico 1\u20130, will face U.S. in CONCACAF Gold Cup final|first=Greg|last=Beacham|location=[[Pasadena, California]]|date=23 July 2017|access-date=26 June 2019|publisher=Chicago Tribune|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190515082240/https://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/soccer/ct-jamaica-mexico-concacaf-gold-cup-20170723-story.html|archive-date=15 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In the final against the US, Jamaica conceded the opening goal at the end of the first half before [[Je-Vaughn Watson]] tied the score in the 50th minute. However, after a goal in the 88th minute from [[Jordan Morris]], the US won the title, and Jamaica finished as runner-up.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/jul/27/gold-cup-final-usa-beat-jamaica-jordan-morris-soccer|title=Gold Cup: USA beat Jamaica in final thanks to Jordan Morris's late winner|first=Tom|last=Dart|date=27 July 2017|access-date=26 June 2019|publisher=The Guardian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190413130418/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/jul/27/gold-cup-final-usa-beat-jamaica-jordan-morris-soccer|archive-date=13 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Rising in FIFA rankings (2020-)===\n\nIn 2020, Jamaica started the year ranked 48th in the FIFA men's ranking.<ref>https://www.fifa.com/fifa-world-ranking/associations/association/JAM/men/</ref>\n\n==Stadium==\n{{Main|Independence Park (Jamaica)}}\n[[File:Independence Park.jpg|thumb|right|200px|National Stadium in 2011]]\nBetween 1926 and 1962. Jamaica played its matches at [[Sabina Park]], which is also home to the [[West Indies cricket team]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reggaeboyzsc.com/interactivecenter.asp?page=history|title=Statistical History of Jamaican Football 1925\u20131989...1994\u201398|access-date=4 June 2019|publisher=reggaeboyzsc.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180405125811/http://www.reggaeboyzsc.com/interactivecenter.asp?page=history|archive-date=5 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1962, the football team moved to Independence Park, which was built for the [[1962 Central American and Caribbean Games]] held after the country gained independence; the first home match was a 6\u20131 victory over Puerto Rico.<ref name=1962CAC/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nlj.gov.jm/MinistryPapers/1962/No.15.pdf|title=Ministry Paper No. 15 National Stadium|first=Glendon|last=Logan|date=20 March 1962|access-date=4 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150610111638/http://www.nlj.gov.jm/MinistryPapers/1962/No.15.pdf|archive-date=10 June 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The stadium is nicknamed ''The Office'' while the team plays.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-19059452|title=Jamaica at 50 gives cause to cheer and reflect|first=Nick|last=Davis|date=4 August 2012|access-date=4 June 2019|publisher=BBC|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190604054913/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-19059452|archive-date=4 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe team has also played at [[Jarrett Park]] and [[Trelawny Stadium]] in the 2008 Caribbean Cup<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/power/5063|title=Reggae Boyz/Grenada Face Off|date=5 December 2008|access-date=12 August 2019|publisher=Jamaica Gleaner}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/power/5098|title=Reggae Boyz Reach Semis|date=8 December 2008|access-date=12 August 2019|publisher=Jamaica Gleaner}}</ref> and the [[Montego Bay Sports Complex]] in the 2014 Caribbean Cup.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/article/sports/20141118/reggae-boyz-win-2014-caribbean-cup|title=Reggae Boyz Win 2014 Caribbean Cup|date=18 November 2014|access-date=12 August 2019|first=Paul|last=Clarke|publisher=Jamaica Gleaner}}</ref>\n\n==Kits==\nThe national team has used four clothing manufacturers that supplied the official kit for Jamaica. The team's first supplier was Italian manufacturer Lanzera in 1995 before it merged with [[Kappa (brand)|Kappa]] a year later. This deal was terminated after the 1998 World Cup.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20081009/sports/sports13.html|title=No new jerseys for fans|date=9 October 2008|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012165238/http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20081009/sports/sports13.html|archive-date=12 October 2008|publisher=Jamaica Gleaner}}</ref> In 2000, the JFF signed a deal with German sporting brand [[Uhlsport]], which lasted until 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20001216/sports/sports4.html|title=JFF signs sweet deal with Uhlsport|date=16 December 2000|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030922104638/http://www.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20001216/sports/sports4.html|archive-date=22 September 2003|publisher=Jamaica Gleaner|access-date=26 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20080421/sports/sports3.html|title=Crucial trip for JFF boss|first=Audley|last=Boyd|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080422095133/http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20080421/sports/sports3.html|archive-date=22 April 2008|publisher=Jamaica Gleaner|access-date=26 June 2019}}</ref> After another three-year contract with Kappa between 2012 and 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballshirtculture.com/Sponsorship/jamaica-sign-kappa-kit-deal.html|title=Jamaica sign Kappa Kit Deal|date=24 January 2012|access-date=28 June 2019|publisher=footballshirtculture.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190628021504/http://www.footballshirtculture.com/Sponsorship/jamaica-sign-kappa-kit-deal.html|archive-date=28 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> the JFF signed a four-year deal with Emiratie sportswear company [[Romai Sports]] for {{USD|4.8 million}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thereggaeboyz.com/jamaica-football-sponsor.html|title=Romai Sportswear is the official clothing sponsor of Jamaica football teams|access-date=28 June 2019|publisher=thereggaeboyz.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190130232338/http://www.thereggaeboyz.com/jamaica-football-sponsor.html|archive-date=30 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Schedule and recent results==\n{{main|Jamaica national football team results}}\nAs of 18 November 2019, the national team has played in [[Jamaica national football team results|547 matches]], with 221 wins, 117 draws, and 209 losses since their first international match in 1925. In total, the team has scored 740 goals and conceded 722 goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.11v11.com/teams/jamaica/|title=Jamaica national football team (Reggae Boyz)|publisher=11v11.com|access-date=23 October 2019}}</ref> Jamaica's highest winning margin is twelve goals, which has been achieved on two occasions: against the [[British Virgin Islands national football team|British Virgin Islands]] in 1994 (12\u20130) and against [[Saint Martin national football team|Saint Martin]] in 2004 (12\u20130).<ref name=JamaicaMatches/> Their longest winning streak is seven wins and their unbeaten record is 22 consecutive official matches.<ref name=JamaicaMatches/>\n\nThe following matches were played or are scheduled to be played in the upcoming 12 months. The local time in Jamaica is shown first. If the local time is different, it will be displayed below.\n\n{{legend2|#bbffbb|Win|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n{{legend2|#FFFFCC|Draw|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n{{legend2|#FFCCCC|Loss|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n\n===2019===\n{{Footballbox collapsible\n|round=[[Exhibition game|Friendly]]\n|date = {{Start date|2019|6|5|df=y}}\n|time = 19:00 ([[UTC\u221205:00|UTC\u22125]])\n|team1 = {{fb-rt|USA}}\n|score = 0\u20131\n|report = https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2019/06/06/world/friendlies/united-states-of-america/jamaica/3013447/\n|team2 = {{fb|JAM}}\n|goals1 = \n|goals2 = [[Shamar Nicholson|Nicholson]] {{goal|60}}\n|location = [[Washington, D.C.]], [[United States]]\n|stadium = [[Audi Field]]\n|attendance = 17,719\n|referee = Kimbett Ward ([[St. Kitts and Nevis Football Association|Saint Kitts and Nevis]])\n|result = W\n|stack = yes\n}}\n{{Footballbox collapsible \n| date = {{Start date|2019|6|17|df=y}}\n| time = 20:30 ([[UTC\u221205:00|UTC\u22125]])\n| round = [[2019 CONCACAF Gold Cup#Group stage|Gold Cup GS]]\n| team1 