uads#Jamaica|Squad]]\n|- bgcolor=silver\n|{{flagicon|MTQ}} [[2017 Caribbean Cup|2017]]||'''Runners-up'''||'''2'''||'''0'''||'''1'''||'''1'''||'''2'''||'''3'''||[[2017 Caribbean Cup squads#Jamaica|Squad]]\n|-class=\"sortbottom\"\n!style=\"color:yellow; background:black;\" |Total||style=\"color:yellow; background:black;\"| 15/18 ||style=\"color:yellow; background:black;\"|60   ||style=\"color:yellow; background:black;\"| 38 ||style=\"color:yellow; background:black;\"|12   ||style=\"color:yellow; background:black;\"| 10 ||style=\"color:yellow; background:black;\"|110  ||style=\"color:yellow; background:black;\"| 45 ||style=\"color:yellow; background:black;\"|\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Association football|Jamaica}}\n* [[National Premier League]] (top league in Jamaica)\n* [[Jamaica national under-20 football team]]\n* [[Jamaica national under-17 football team]]\n* [[Football in Jamaica]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=upper-alpha}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Jamaica national association football team}}\n* [https://www.jff.live/ Jamaican Football Federation]\n* [https://www.fifa.com/associations/association=jam/index.html Jamaica FIFA profile]\n\n{{Jamaica national football team}}\n{{CFU Caribbean Cup Winners}}\n{{Football in Jamaica}}\n{{CONCACAF teams}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title=Jamaica FIFA World Cup squads\n| bg          = #FED100\n| fg          = #009638\n| bordercolor = black\n|list1=\n{{Jamaica squad 1998 FIFA World Cup}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title=Jamaica CONCACAF Gold Cup squads\n| bg          = #FED100\n| fg          = #009638\n| bordercolor = black\n|list1=\n{{Jamaica squad 1991 CONCACAF Gold Cup}}\n{{Jamaica squad 1993 CONCACAF Gold Cup}}\n{{Jamaica squad 1998 CONCACAF Gold Cup}}\n{{Jamaica squad 2000 CONCACAF Gold Cup}}\n{{Jamaica squad 2005 CONCACAF Gold Cup}}\n{{Jamaica squad 2009 CONCACAF Gold Cup}}\n{{Jamaica squad 2011 CONCACAF Gold Cup}}\n{{Jamaica squad 2015 CONCACAF Gold Cup}}\n{{Jamaica squad 2017 CONCACAF Gold Cup}}\n{{Jamaica squad 2019 CONCACAF Gold Cup}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title=Jamaica Copa Am\u00e9rica squads\n| bg          = #FED100\n| fg          = #009638\n| bordercolor = black\n|list1=\n{{Jamaica squad 2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n{{Jamaica squad Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario}}\n}}\n{{National sports teams of Jamaica}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jamaica National Football Team}}\n[[Category:Jamaica national football team| ]]\n[[Category:Caribbean national association football teams]]\n[[Category:National sports teams of Jamaica|Football]]\n[[Category:Football in Jamaica]]\n", "name_user": "69.127.134.251", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eContinental finals appearances (2010\u20132019))", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jamaica_national_football_team"}
{"title_page": "NCBA Group Plc", "text_new": "{{short description|Kenyan financial services conglomerate}}\n{{inuse}}\n\n{{EngvarB|date = May 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date = May 2019}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name          = NCBA Group Plc\n| logo          = \n| type \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0  = [[Public company|Public]]: [[Nairobi Stock Exchange|NSE]]: '''NNIC''' \u00a0\n| foundation    = {{Start date and years ago|1959|09|29|df=y}}\n| location      = [[Nairobi]], [[Kenya]]\n| key_people    = '''J.P.M.Ndegwa'''<br/> [[Chairman|Group Chairman]]<br/>'''[[John Gachora]]'''<br/>[[CEO|Group CEO]]\n| industry      = [[Banking]] and [[Finance]]\n| products      = [[Loans]], [[Mortgages]] [[Investments]], [[Debit cards]], [[Credit Cards]] \n| revenue       = {{profit}}Aftertax:US$58 million (KES:6.09 billion) (2019)<ref name=\"Data\"/>\n| assets        = US$4.43 billion (KES:464.89 billion) (2019)<ref name=\"Data\"/>\n| num_employees = 1,302 (2018)\n| homepage      = [https://www.ncbagroup.com/ NCBA Group]\n|trading_name = |traded_as = {{KN|NINC}}}}\n\n'''NCBA Group Plc''', is a financial services [[conglomerate (company)|conglomerate]] in [[East Africa]]. The Group's headquarters are located in [[Nairobi]], Kenya, with subsidiaries in [[Kenya]], [[Tanzania]], and [[Uganda]].<ref name=\"2R\">{{cite web|url=https://businesstoday.co.ke/nic-cba-to-begin-life-as-ncba-group-plc/ |title=NIC, CBA Cement Partnership Becoming NCBA Group Plc |publisher=Business Today Kenya |date=1 October 2019 | author=Kevin Namunwa |access-date=15 April 2020 |place=Nairobi}}</ref>\n\n==Location==\nThe group's headquarters are located along Mara Road, in the neighborhood called [[Upper Hill, Nairobi|Upper Hill]], in [[Nairobi]], the capital city of Kenya. The geographical coordinates of the group's headquarters are:01\u00b017'52.0\"S, 36\u00b048'46.0\"E (Latitude:-1.297778; Longitude:36.812778).<ref name=\"3R\">{{google maps|access-date=15 April 2020 | url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/1%C2%B017'52.0%22S+36%C2%B048'46.0%22E/@-1.2977778,36.8127778,392m/data=!3m2!1e3!4b1!4m2!3m1!1s0x0:0x0 |title=Location of the headquarters of NCBA Group Plc}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nNCBA Group Plc is a large financial services organization in East Africa, with assets valued at over US$4.43 billion (KES:464.89 billion) as of December 2019. Shareholders' equity at that time was valued at approximately US$661 million (KES:69.416 billion).<ref name=\"Data\">{{cite web|url=https://ncbagroup.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/NCBA-Group-PLC-2019-Audited-Financial-Results.pdf |title=Audited Financial Results For The Year Ended 31 December 2019 |publisher=NCBA Group |date=24 March 2020 | author=NCBA Group |access-date=14 April 2020 |location=Nairobi}}</ref> The group functions as a non-operating [[holding company]] for its subsidiaries in the region. As of October 2019, the group serviced an estimated 40 million customers in four East African countries.<ref name=\"2R\"/>\n\n==History==\n\n=== 1959-1990 === \nNational Industrial Credit (NIC) was incorporated in Kenya on 29 September 1959, when [[South Africa]]-based [[Standard Bank (historic)|Standard Bank]] and [[United Kingdom]]-based Mercantile Credit Limited jointly formed the company to provide hire purchase and installment credit finance facilities in East Africa. Standard Bank held 40 percent of the venture while Mercantile Credit held the remaining 60 percent.<ref name=\"4R\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.aim25.ac.uk/cgi-bin/vcdf/detail?coll_id=19613&inst_id=118&nv1=browse&nv2=sub|title = National Industrial Credit Corporation: Corporate|date = |accessdate = 2015-10-05|website = |publisher = [[AIM25]]|last = |first = }}</ref>\n\nIn 1971, NIC became a public company and was listed on the then [[Nairobi Stock Exchange]] (NSE). [[Barclays Bank (Kenya)| Barclays Bank of Kenya Limited]] (BBK) acquired 51 percent of NIC\u2019s total shares through the acquisition of Mercantile in the 1970s and Standard\u2019s NIC shares in the 1980s.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== 1991-1999 ===\nBetween 1993 and 1996, BBK divested its shares, selling 38 percent of its shares to the public in 1994 through a [[secondary market offering]] and the remaining 20 percent in 1996 to the First Chartered Securities Group (FCS). Because of changing trends, regulatory requirements in the Kenyan banking industry, and the need to meet growing customer requirements, NIC obtained a commercial banking license from the [[Central Bank of Kenya]] in September 1995.<ref name=\"5R\">{{cite web|title=Conversions to Commercial Banks in Kenya 1994 - 2008 |date=2017 | url=https://www.centralbank.go.ke/commercial-banks/conversions/ |publisher=[[Central Bank of Kenya]] |author=Central Bank of Kenya |access-date=15 April 2020 |location=Nairobi}}</ref>\n\nTo effectively diversify into mainstream commercial banking, NIC merged in November 1997 with African Mercantile Bank Limited, which was then owned by FCS, by way of a share swap. The purpose of this merger was to allow NIC to enhance its market position, provide a broader and more efficient range of services to its customers, and increase the returns to shareholders.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== 2000-2008 ===\nIn 2006, NIC established an [[investment bank]] NIC Capital as a wholly owned subsidiary. In 2008, NIC through its subsidiary NIC Capital acquired a 91 percent stake in Solid Securities Limited and subsequently rebranded it to NIC Securities Limited. This acquisition gave NIC Bank Group a seat at the NSE.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== 2009-To Date ===\nIn 2009 NIC Bank Group established NIC Insurance Agents to offer insurance brokerage and bancassurance services. In the same year, the Group made its first expansion outside Kenya through its acquisition of a 51 percent share of Savings and Finance Commercial Bank, a medium size bank in Tanzania. In December 2010, the Savings and Finance Commercial Bank was renamed [[NIC Bank Tanzania|NIC Bank Tanzania Limited]]. In 2012, the group established operations in [[Uganda]] through [[NC Bank Uganda]]. This was a [[greenfield investment]].<ref name=\"6R\">{{cite web| url=https://www.monitor.co.ug/Business/Finance/NIC-CBA-parent-banks-merger-negotiations/688608-4888160-2y77b2z/index.html | title=NIC, CBA parent banks in merger negotiations |date=10 December 2018 |newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] |access-date=15 April 2020 |author=Ismail Musa Ladu |location=Kampala}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, NIC Group announced that it would be merging with [[Commercial Bank of Africa Group]] (CBA) creating Kenya's third-biggest bank.<ref name=\"7R\">{{cite web|date=7 December 2018 |url=https://kenyanwallstreet.com/nic-bank-cba-group-in-merger-talks-to-create-3rd-largest-lender/ |title=NIC Bank and CBA Group In Merger Talks to Create 3rd Largest Kenyan Lender |access-date=15 April 2020 |publisher=The Kenyan Wall Street |author=The Kenyan Wall Street |location=Nairobi}}</ref> The merger involved the transfer of 100 percent of the shares of CBA Group by its shareholders to NIC Group in exchange for 53 percent of the newly formed group making the deal a [[Reverse takeover|reverse merger]].<ref name=\"8R\">{{cite web|title=CBA, NIC confirm merger plan as unified banks to list on NSE |date=31 January 2019 | url=https://www.businessdailyafrica.com/corporate/companies/CBA--NIC-confirm-merger-plan-as-unified-bank-to-list-on-NSE/4003102-4959696-swmc9a/index.html |newspaper=[[Business Daily Africa]] | author=Victor Juma |access-date=15 April 2020 |place=Nairobi}}</ref>\n\nThe Transaction was approved by the Kenyan regulators and shareholders by April 2019.<ref name=\"9R\">{{cite web| url=https://www.businessdailyafrica.com/news/Regulator-approves-CBA-NIC-merger/539546-5112672-52vish/index.html |title=Regulator approves CBA-NIC merger on condition of employees retention | date=13 May 2019 |newspaper=[[Business Daily Africa]] |\nauthor=Patrick Alushula |access-date=15 April 2020 | location=Nairobi}}</ref><ref name=\"10R\">{{cite web|date=17 April 2019 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-nic-bank-m-a-cba/kenyas-nic-group-shareholders-back-merger-with-cba-idUSKCN1RT1ML |title=Kenya's NIC Group shareholders back merger with CBA |publisher=Reuters |author=Omar Mohammed |editor=Louise Heavens and Emelia Sithole-Matarise |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> As of May 2019, the merged group was still operating two sets of banks in Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania but was in the process of seeking regulatory approval to merge these business so that they can have one bank in each country and a group rebranding.<ref name=\"11R\">{{cite web|newspaper=[[Daily Nation]] |url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/Management-shakeup-at-CBA-and-NIC-banks/1056-5116784-kug187z/ |title=John Gachora picked to head NIC, CBA merged outfit |date=16 May 2019 |author=Paul Wafula |access-date=15 April 2020 |place=Nairobi}}</ref>\n\n==Member companies==\nNCBA Group maintains the following subsidiaries, as of April 2020.\n\n# [[NCBA Bank Kenya]]: [[Banking|Retail banking]]: Nairobi, Kenya \u2013 100 percent shareholding \u2013 A [[commercial bank]] in Kenya, serving individuals and businesses, focusing mainly on large corporations. This is the flagship company of the group.\n# NCBA Investment Bank Limited: [[Investment banking]]: Nairobi, Kenya \u2013 NCBA Investment Bank was established in 2005 to offer investment banking services. The group owns all the shares in the unit.<ref name=\"12R\">{{cite web|newspaper=[[Business Daily Africa]] |title=NIC raises stake in stockbrokerage unit |\nurl=https://www.businessdailyafrica.com/Corporate-News/NIC-raises-stake-in-stockbrokerage-unit-/-/539550/2314758/-/x6uos6/-/index.html |author=Victor Juma |access-date=15 April 2020 |place=Nairobi}}</ref>\n# NCBA Insurance Agents: [[Bancassurance]] \u2013 Nairobi, Kenya  \u2013 NCBA Insurance Agents offers Bancassurance services. NCBA Group owns all of the company. \n# [[NCBA Bank Tanzania]]: [[Banking|Retail banking]]: [[Dar es Salaam]], Tanzania.<ref name=\"13R\">{{cite web|date=20 December 2010 |newspaper=[[The EastAfrican]] |access-date=15 April 2020 | url=https://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/business/NIC%20Bank%20acquires%20Savings%20and%20%20Finance%20invests%20$6m%20in%20SMEs/-/2560/1074810/-/hljw6kz/-/index.html |title=NIC Bank acquires Savings and Finance, invests $6m in SMEs |author=Leonard Magomba | location=Nairobi}}</ref> After a successful rights issue in 2013, NIC Group's interest in its Tanzanian subsidiary rose from 51 percent to 68.97 percent.<ref name=\"14R\">{{cite web| url=http://www.businessdailyafrica.com/Corporate-News/NIC-taps-Ecobank-finance-chief-as-it-ups-Tanzania-stake/-/539550/2211968/-/xqbxg1/-/index.html |title=NIC taps Ecobank finance chief as it ups Tanzania stake |date=18 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Business Daily Africa]] |access-date=15 April 2020 |author=George Ngigi |location=Nairobi}}</ref>\n# [[NCBA Bank Uganda]]: Retail banking: [[Kampala]], [[Uganda]].  The group owns all of the shares of the unit.\n# [[NCBA Bank Rwanda]]: Retail banking: [[Kigali]], [[Rwanda]].\n\n==Branch network==\nAs at October 2014, NIC Bank Group's branch network was as follows<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.nic-bank.com/main/branchatm-location/| title = NIC Bank Branch Network | accessdate = 22 October 2014 | publisher = NIC Bank Group}}</ref><ref name=\"NIC Rights Issue\">{{Cite web | url = http://www.nic-bank.com/main/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/NIC-Rights-Issue-IM.pdf | title = Information Memorandum: NIC Rights Issue | date = 2 October 2014 | accessdate = 23 October 2014 | publisher = NIC Bank Group}}</ref>\n\n* [[NIC Bank|NIC Bank (Kenya)]]  \u2013 24\n* [[Kenya Post Office Savings Bank]] as agents<ref name=\"Information Memorandum\" /> \u2013 94\n* [[NIC Bank Tanzania]] \u2013 6\n* [[NC Bank Uganda]] \u2013 1\n\n==Ownership==\nThe [[stock]] of NCBA Bank Group listed on the [[Nairobi Stock Exchange|NSE]], where it trades under the symbol NINC. {{asof|2019|October|01|df=UK}}, the largest shareholders in the Group's stock are depicted in the table below:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nicgroup.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/NIC-Group-PLC-Circular-2019.pdf|title=Circular to shareholders - Proposed Merger between Commercial Bank of Africa Limited and NIC Group Plc|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=NIC Group Plc|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=29 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto\"\n|+NCBA Bank Group Stock Ownership\n! style=\"width:2em;\" |Rank !!Name of Owner!!Percentage Ownership\n|-\n|1||Enke Investments Ltd||13.21\n|-\n|2||Ropat Nominees Limited||11.93\n|-\n|3||Livingstone Registrars Ltd A/C No. 1||10.56\n|-\n|4||First Chartered Securities Limited||7.45\n|-\n|5||Yana Investments Limited||5.91\n|-\n|6||ICEA LION Asset Management Limited||4.23\n|-\n|7||Others||46.71\n|-\n| ||'''Total'''||'''100.00'''\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[NIC Bank|NIC Bank Kenya]]\n* [[NIC Bank Tanzania]]\n* [[NIC Bank Uganda]]\n* [[Nairobi Stock Exchange]]\n* [[Central Bank of Kenya]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.ncbagroup.com/  NCBA Group Plc Homepage]\n* [http://www.nse.co.ke/newsite/  Nairobi Stock Exchange Website]\n* [http://www.centralbank.go.ke/  Central Bank of Kenya]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120406133411/http://www.centralbank.go.ke/financialsystem/banks/Register.aspx List of Licensed Commercial Banks in Kenya]\n* [https://www.monitor.co.ug/Business/Markets/688606-1384146-pasaga/index.html/ Bank of Uganda Licenses Two New Banks] As of 11 April 2012.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Banking in Kenya}}\n{{coord|01|17|52|S|36|48|46|E|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Banks of Kenya]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Nairobi Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Nairobi]]\n[[Category:Banks established in 1959]]\n[[Category:1959 establishments in Kenya]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Kenyan financial services conglomerate}}\n{{inuse}}\n\n{{EngvarB|date = May 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date = May 2019}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name          = NCBA Group Plc\n| logo          = \n| type \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0  = [[Public company|Public]]: [[Nairobi Stock Exchange|NSE]]: '''NNIC''' \u00a0\n| foundation    = {{Start date and years ago|1959|09|29|df=y}}\n| location      = [[Nairobi]], [[Kenya]]\n| key_people    = '''J.P.M.Ndegwa'''<br/> [[Chairman|Group Chairman]]<br/>'''[[John Gachora]]'''<br/>[[CEO|Group CEO]]\n| industry      = [[Banking]] and [[Finance]]\n| products      = [[Loans]], [[Mortgages]] [[Investments]], [[Debit cards]], [[Credit Cards]] \n| revenue       = {{profit}}Aftertax:US$58 million (KES:6.09 billion) (2019)<ref name=\"Data\"/>\n| assets        = US$4.43 billion (KES:464.89 billion) (2019)<ref name=\"Data\"/>\n| num_employees = 1,302 (2018)\n| homepage      = [https://www.ncbagroup.com/ NCBA Group]\n|trading_name = |traded_as = {{KN|NINC}}}}\n\n'''NCBA Group Plc''', is a financial services [[conglomerate (company)|conglomerate]] in [[East Africa]]. The Group's headquarters are located in [[Nairobi]], Kenya, with subsidiaries in [[Kenya]], [[Tanzania]], and [[Uganda]].<ref name=\"2R\">{{cite web|url=https://businesstoday.co.ke/nic-cba-to-begin-life-as-ncba-group-plc/ |title=NIC, CBA Cement Partnership Becoming NCBA Group Plc |publisher=Business Today Kenya |date=1 October 2019 | author=Kevin Namunwa |access-date=15 April 2020 |place=Nairobi}}</ref>\n\n==Location==\nThe group's headquarters are located along Mara Road, in the neighborhood called [[Upper Hill, Nairobi|Upper Hill]], in [[Nairobi]], the capital city of Kenya. The geographical coordinates of the group's headquarters are:01\u00b017'52.0\"S, 36\u00b048'46.0\"E (Latitude:-1.297778; Longitude:36.812778).<ref name=\"3R\">{{google maps|access-date=15 April 2020 | url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/1%C2%B017'52.0%22S+36%C2%B048'46.0%22E/@-1.2977778,36.8127778,392m/data=!3m2!1e3!4b1!4m2!3m1!1s0x0:0x0 |title=Location of the headquarters of NCBA Group Plc}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nNCBA Group Plc is a large financial services organization in East Africa, with assets valued at over US$4.43 billion (KES:464.89 billion) as of December 2019. Shareholders' equity at that time was valued at approximately US$661 million (KES:69.416 billion).<ref name=\"Data\">{{cite web|url=https://ncbagroup.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/NCBA-Group-PLC-2019-Audited-Financial-Results.pdf |title=Audited Financial Results For The Year Ended 31 December 2019 |publisher=NCBA Group |date=24 March 2020 | author=NCBA Group |access-date=14 April 2020 |location=Nairobi}}</ref> The group functions as a non-operating [[holding company]] for its subsidiaries in the region. As of October 2019, the group serviced an estimated 40 million customers in four East African countries.<ref name=\"2R\"/>\n\n==History==\n\n=== 1959-1990 === \nNational Industrial Credit (NIC) was incorporated in Kenya on 29 September 1959, when [[South Africa]]-based [[Standard Bank (historic)|Standard Bank]] and [[United Kingdom]]-based Mercantile Credit Limited jointly formed the company to provide hire purchase and installment credit finance facilities in East Africa. Standard Bank held 40 percent of the venture while Mercantile Credit held the remaining 60 percent.<ref name=\"4R\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.aim25.ac.uk/cgi-bin/vcdf/detail?coll_id=19613&inst_id=118&nv1=browse&nv2=sub|title = National Industrial Credit Corporation: Corporate|date = |accessdate = 2015-10-05|website = |publisher = [[AIM25]]|last = |first = }}</ref>\n\nIn 1971, NIC became a public company and was listed on the then [[Nairobi Stock Exchange]] (NSE). [[Barclays Bank (Kenya)| Barclays Bank of Kenya Limited]] (BBK) acquired 51 percent of NIC\u2019s total shares through the acquisition of Mercantile in the 1970s and Standard\u2019s NIC shares in the 1980s.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== 1991-1999 ===\nBetween 1993 and 1996, BBK divested its shares, selling 38 percent of its shares to the public in 1994 through a [[secondary market offering]] and the remaining 20 percent in 1996 to the First Chartered Securities Group (FCS). Because of changing trends, regulatory requirements in the Kenyan banking industry, and the need to meet growing customer requirements, NIC obtained a commercial banking license from the [[Central Bank of Kenya]] in September 1995.<ref name=\"5R\">{{cite web|title=Conversions to Commercial Banks in Kenya 1994 - 2008 |date=2017 | url=https://www.centralbank.go.ke/commercial-banks/conversions/ |publisher=[[Central Bank of Kenya]] |author=Central Bank of Kenya |access-date=15 April 2020 |location=Nairobi}}</ref>\n\nTo effectively diversify into mainstream commercial banking, NIC merged in November 1997 with African Mercantile Bank Limited, which was then owned by FCS, by way of a share swap. The purpose of this merger was to allow NIC to enhance its market position, provide a broader and more efficient range of services to its customers, and increase the returns to shareholders.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== 2000-2008 ===\nIn 2006, NIC established an [[investment bank]] NIC Capital as a wholly owned subsidiary. In 2008, NIC through its subsidiary NIC Capital acquired a 91 percent stake in Solid Securities Limited and subsequently rebranded it to NIC Securities Limited. This acquisition gave NIC Bank Group a seat at the NSE.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== 2009-To Date ===\nIn 2009 NIC Bank Group established NIC Insurance Agents to offer insurance brokerage and bancassurance services. In the same year, the Group made its first expansion outside Kenya through its acquisition of a 51 percent share of Savings and Finance Commercial Bank, a medium size bank in Tanzania. In December 2010, the Savings and Finance Commercial Bank was renamed [[NIC Bank Tanzania|NIC Bank Tanzania Limited]]. In 2012, the group established operations in [[Uganda]] through [[NC Bank Uganda]]. This was a [[greenfield investment]].<ref name=\"6R\">{{cite web| url=https://www.monitor.co.ug/Business/Finance/NIC-CBA-parent-banks-merger-negotiations/688608-4888160-2y77b2z/index.html | title=NIC, CBA parent banks in merger negotiations |date=10 December 2018 |newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] |access-date=15 April 2020 |author=Ismail Musa Ladu |location=Kampala}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, NIC Group announced that it would be merging with [[Commercial Bank of Africa Group]] (CBA) creating Kenya's third-biggest bank.<ref name=\"7R\">{{cite web|date=7 December 2018 |url=https://kenyanwallstreet.com/nic-bank-cba-group-in-merger-talks-to-create-3rd-largest-lender/ |title=NIC Bank and CBA Group In Merger Talks to Create 3rd Largest Kenyan Lender |access-date=15 April 2020 |publisher=The Kenyan Wall Street |author=The Kenyan Wall Street |location=Nairobi}}</ref> The merger involved the transfer of 100 percent of the shares of CBA Group by its shareholders to NIC Group in exchange for 53 percent of the newly formed group making the deal a [[Reverse takeover|reverse merger]].<ref name=\"8R\">{{cite web|title=CBA, NIC confirm merger plan as unified banks to list on NSE |date=31 January 2019 | url=https://www.businessdailyafrica.com/corporate/companies/CBA--NIC-confirm-merger-plan-as-unified-bank-to-list-on-NSE/4003102-4959696-swmc9a/index.html |newspaper=[[Business Daily Africa]] | author=Victor Juma |access-date=15 April 2020 |place=Nairobi}}</ref>\n\nThe Transaction was approved by the Kenyan regulators and shareholders by April 2019.<ref name=\"9R\">{{cite web| url=https://www.businessdailyafrica.com/news/Regulator-approves-CBA-NIC-merger/539546-5112672-52vish/index.html |title=Regulator approves CBA-NIC merger on condition of employees retention | date=13 May 2019 |newspaper=[[Business Daily Africa]] |\nauthor=Patrick Alushula |access-date=15 April 2020 | location=Nairobi}}</ref><ref name=\"10R\">{{cite web|date=17 April 2019 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-nic-bank-m-a-cba/kenyas-nic-group-shareholders-back-merger-with-cba-idUSKCN1RT1ML |title=Kenya's NIC Group shareholders back merger with CBA |publisher=Reuters |author=Omar Mohammed |editor=Louise Heavens and Emelia Sithole-Matarise |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> As of May 2019, the merged group was still operating two sets of banks in Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania but was in the process of seeking regulatory approval to merge these business so that they can have one bank in each country and a group rebranding.<ref name=\"11R\">{{cite web|newspaper=[[Daily Nation]] |url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/Management-shakeup-at-CBA-and-NIC-banks/1056-5116784-kug187z/ |title=John Gachora picked to head NIC, CBA merged outfit |date=16 May 2019 |author=Paul Wafula |access-date=15 April 2020 |place=Nairobi}}</ref>\n\n==Member companies==\nNCBA Group maintains the following subsidiaries, as of April 2020.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n# [[NCBA Bank Kenya]]: [[Banking|Retail banking]]: Nairobi, Kenya \u2013 100 percent shareholding \u2013 A [[commercial bank]] in Kenya, serving individuals and businesses, focusing mainly on large corporations. This is the flagship company of the group.\n# NCBA Investment Bank Limited: [[Investment banking]]: Nairobi, Kenya \u2013 NCBA Investment Bank was established in 2005 to offer investment banking services. The group owns all the shares in the unit. After the Group's merger with CBA, the business of NIC Capital Securities (a [[Brokerage|Securities brokerage]] unit formally known as Solid Investment Securities) and CBA Capital were merged to this business unit.<ref name=\"12R\">{{cite web|\nurl=https://www.businessdailyafrica.com/Corporate-News/NIC-raises-stake-in-stockbrokerage-unit-/-/539550/2314758/-/x6uos6/-/index.html |title=NIC raises stake in stockbrokerage unit |newspaper=[[Business Daily Africa]] |author=Victor Juma |access-date=15 April 2020 |place=Nairobi}}</ref>\n# NCBA Insurance Agents: [[Bancassurance]] \u2013 Nairobi, Kenya  \u2013 NCBA Insurance Agents offers Bancassurance services. NCBA Group owns all of the company. \n# [[NCBA Bank Tanzania]]: [[Banking|Retail banking]]: [[Dar es Salaam]], Tanzania.<ref name=\"13R\">{{cite web|date=20 December 20210 |newspaper=[[The EastAfrican]] |access-date=15 April 2020 | url=https://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/business/NIC%20Bank%20acquires%20Savings%20and%20%20Finance%20invests%20$6m%20in%20SMEs/-/2560/1074810/-/hljw6kz/-/index.html |title=NIC Bank acquires Savings and Finance, invests $6m in SMEs |author=Leonard Magomba | location=Nairobi}}</ref> After a successful rights issue in 2013, NIC Group's interest in its Tanzanian subsidiary rose from 51 percent to 68.97 percent.<ref name=\"14R\">{{cite web| url=http://www.businessdailyafrica.com/Corporate-News/NIC-taps-Ecobank-finance-chief-as-it-ups-Tanzania-stake/-/539550/2211968/-/xqbxg1/-/index.html |title=NIC taps Ecobank finance chief as it ups Tanzania stake |date=18 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Business Daily Africa]] |access-date=15 April 2020 |author=George Ngigi |location=Nairobi}}</ref>\n# [[NCBA Bank Uganda]]: Retail banking: [[Kampala]], [[Uganda]].  The group owns all of the shares of the unit.\n# [[NCBA Bank Rwanda]]: Retail banking: [[Kigali]], [[Rwanda]].\n\n==Branch network==\nAs at October 2014, NIC Bank Group's branch network was as follows<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.nic-bank.com/main/branchatm-location/| title = NIC Bank Branch Network | accessdate = 22 October 2014 | publisher = NIC Bank Group}}</ref><ref name=\"NIC Rights Issue\">{{Cite web | url = http://www.nic-bank.com/main/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/NIC-Rights-Issue-IM.pdf | title = Information Memorandum: NIC Rights Issue | date = 2 October 2014 | accessdate = 23 October 2014 | publisher = NIC Bank Group}}</ref>\n\n* [[NIC Bank|NIC Bank (Kenya)]]  \u2013 24\n* [[Kenya Post Office Savings Bank]] as agents<ref name=\"Information Memorandum\" /> \u2013 94\n* [[NIC Bank Tanzania]] \u2013 6\n* [[NC Bank Uganda]] \u2013 1\n\n==Ownership==\nThe [[stock]] of NCBA Bank Group listed on the [[Nairobi Stock Exchange|NSE]], where it trades under the symbol NINC. {{asof|2019|October|01|df=UK}}, the largest shareholders in the Group's stock are depicted in the table below:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nicgroup.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/NIC-Group-PLC-Circular-2019.pdf|title=Circular to shareholders - Proposed Merger between Commercial Bank of Africa Limited and NIC Group Plc|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=NIC Group Plc|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=29 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto\"\n|+NCBA Bank Group Stock Ownership\n! style=\"width:2em;\" |Rank !!Name of Owner!!Percentage Ownership\n|-\n|1||Enke Investments Ltd||13.21\n|-\n|2||Ropat Nominees Limited||11.93\n|-\n|3||Livingstone Registrars Ltd A/C No. 1||10.56\n|-\n|4||First Chartered Securities Limited||7.45\n|-\n|5||Yana Investments Limited||5.91\n|-\n|6||ICEA LION Asset Management Limited||4.23\n|-\n|7||Others||46.71\n|-\n| ||'''Total'''||'''100.00'''\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[NIC Bank|NIC Bank Kenya]]\n* [[NIC Bank Tanzania]]\n* [[NIC Bank Uganda]]\n* [[Nairobi Stock Exchange]]\n* [[Central Bank of Kenya]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.ncbagroup.com/  NCBA Group Plc Homepage]\n* [http://www.nse.co.ke/newsite/  Nairobi Stock Exchange Website]\n* [http://www.centralbank.go.ke/  Central Bank of Kenya]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120406133411/http://www.centralbank.go.ke/financialsystem/banks/Register.aspx List of Licensed Commercial Banks in Kenya]\n* [https://www.monitor.co.ug/Business/Markets/688606-1384146-pasaga/index.html/ Bank of Uganda Licenses Two New Banks] As of 11 April 2012.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Banking in Kenya}}\n{{coord|01|17|52|S|36|48|46|E|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Banks of Kenya]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Nairobi Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Nairobi]]\n[[Category:Banks established in 1959]]\n[[Categ