{"title_page": "Joseph T. Palastra Jr.", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= Joseph T. Palastra Jr.\n|image= Joseph Thomas Palastra JR.jpg\n|image_size= \n|alt= \n|caption= General Joseph T. Palastra Jr.\n|nickname= \n|birth_date= {{birth date|1931|11|10}}\n|birth_place= [[Kittery, Maine]]<ref name=obit>{{cite web|url=http://www.adamsfuneralhome.net/obituaries/Gen-Joseph-Palastra/#!/Obituary|title=Gen. Joseph Thomas Palastra Jr.|work=Gen. Joseph Thomas Palastra Jr. Obituary}}</ref>\n|death_date= {{death date and age|2015|03|03|1931|11|10}} \n|death_place= [[Highlandville, Missouri|Highlandville]], Missouri\n|allegiance= United States\n|branch= [[United States Army]]\n|serviceyears= 1954\u20131989\n|rank= [[General (United States)|General]]\n|servicenumber= \n|unit= \n|commands= [[United States Army Forces Command]]<br/>[[I Corps (United States)|I Corps]]<br/>[[5th Infantry Division (United States)|5th Infantry Division (Mechanized)]]<br/>3rd Brigade, [[101st Airborne Division]]<br/>[[12th Infantry Regiment (United States)|1st Battalion, 12th Infantry Regiment]]\n|battles= [[Vietnam War]]\n|awards= [[Defense Distinguished Service Medal]] (2)<br/>[[Army Distinguished Service Medal]]<br/>[[Silver Star]]<br/>[[Legion of Merit]]<br/>[[Bronze Star Medal]] (3)\n|relations= \n|laterwork= \n}}\n'''Joseph Thomas Palastra Jr.''' (November 10, 1931 \u2013 March 3, 2015) was a [[United States Army]] four-star general who served as Commanding General, [[United States Army Forces Command]] from 1986 to 1989. During his tenure, in 1987, the title was changed to Commander in Chief, Forces Command. He was inducted into the Ranger Hall of Fame, class of 2010.\n\n==Military career==\nA native of [[New Hampshire]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NVFAAQAAIAAJ&q=Palastra,+Joseph+T+1931&dq=Palastra,+Joseph+T+1931&hl=en&ei=aqKPTYK9HsSC0QHxuqycCw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAQ|title=Supplement to Who's who in America|work=google.com}}</ref> Palastra began his career as a second lieutenant after graduating from the [[United States Military Academy]] in 1954. Palastra also holds a Master of Business Administration from [[Auburn University]]. His military education includes the Infantry Officer Basic and Advanced Courses, the United States Army [[Command and General Staff College]] and the [[Air War College]].\n\nPalastra commanded [[I Corps (United States)|I Corps]] and [[Fort Lewis]], Washington. His other key assignments include Commanding General, [[5th Infantry Division (United States)|5th Infantry Division (Mechanized)]] and [[Fort Polk]], Louisiana; Chief of Staff, [[Eighth United States Army]]/[[United States Forces Korea]]; and Deputy Commander in Chief/Chief of Staff, [[United States Pacific Command]], [[Camp H.M. Smith]], Hawaii.\n\nIn 1968 and 1969 Palastra served in Vietnam as Commander, B Company, 4th Aviation Battalion, and as Commander, [[12th Infantry Regiment (United States)|1st Battalion, 12th Infantry Regiment]], in Vietnam's highlands. Palastra was a war-plans staff officer in the Office of the Deputy Chief of Staff for Military Operations, Washington, D.C., and, after attending the [[Air War College]], returned to Washington to serve as a force structure analyst in the Office of the Chief of Staff.\n\nPalastra has also commanded the 3rd Brigade of the [[101st Airborne Division]] at [[Fort Campbell]], Kentucky, and served as Deputy Director for Estimates in the [[Defense Intelligence Agency]].\n\n==Awards and decorations==\n{|\n|[[File:Combat Infantry Badge.svg|125px]]\n|[[Combat Infantryman Badge]]\n|-\n|[[File:Army Senior Aviator.png|120px]]\n|[[United States Aviator Badge|Army Senior Aviator Badge]]\n|-\n|[[File:Ranger Tab.svg|80px]]\n|[[Ranger tab]]\n|-\n|[[File:USAFSeniorParatrooper.jpg|80px]]\n|[[Parachutist Badge (United States)|Senior Parachutist Badge]]\n|-\n|[[File:Office of the Secretary of Defense Identification Badge.png|80px]]\n|[[Office of the Secretary of Defense Identification Badge]]\n|-\n|[[File:United States Army Staff Identification Badge.png|80px]]\n|[[Army Staff Identification Badge]]\n|}\n{|\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=oak|name=Defense Distinguished Service ribbon|width=60}}\n|[[Defense Distinguished Service Medal]] with one bronze [[oak leaf cluster]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Distinguished Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Army Distinguished Service Medal]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Silver Star BAR.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Silver Star]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Legion of Merit ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Legion of Merit]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Bronze Star ribbon.svg|width=60}}<span style=\"position:relative; top: 0px; left: -48px; display: inline-block; width: 0;\">[[File:\"V\" device, brass.svg|12px]]</span><span style=\"position:relative; top: 0px; left: -36px; display: inline-block; width: 0;\">[[File:Bronze oakleaf-3d.svg|14px]]</span><span style=\"position:relative; top: 0px; left: -24px; display: inline-block; width: 0;\">[[File:Bronze oakleaf-3d.svg|14px]]</span>\n|[[Bronze Star]] with [[\"V\" device]] and two oak leaf clusters\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=oak|ribbon=Meritorious Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Meritorious Service Medal (United States)|Meritorious Service Medal]] with oak leaf cluster\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=Air Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}<span style=\"position:relative; top: 0px; left: -36px; display: inline-block; width: 0;\">[[File:Award numeral 8.png|12px]]</span>\n|[[Air Medal]] with bronze [[award numeral]] 8\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=United States Army and U.S. Air Force Presidential Unit Citation ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Presidential Unit Citation (United States)|Army Presidential Unit Citation]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=National Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[National Defense Service Medal]] with one bronze [[service star]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Armed Forces Expeditionary Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}<span style=\"position:relative; top: 0px; left: -41px; display: inline-block; width: 0;\">[[File:Bronze-service-star-3d.png|11px]]</span><span style=\"position:relative; top: 0px; left: -30px; display: inline-block; width: 0;\">[[File:Bronze-service-star-3d.png|11px]]</span>\n|[[Armed Forces Expeditionary Medal]] with one service star\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Army Service Ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Army Service Ribbon]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=numeral|ribbon=Army Overseas Service Ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Overseas Service Ribbon#Army|Army Overseas Service Ribbon]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=Vietnamese Gallantry Cross ribbon.svg|width=60}}<span style=\"position:relative; top: 0px; left: -37px; display: inline-block; width: 0;\">[[File:Bronze-service-star-3d.png|15px]]</span>\n|[[Vietnam Gallantry Cross]] with bronze star\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=|type=|ribbon=Vietnam Campaign Medal ribbon with 60- clasp.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Vietnam Campaign Medal]]\n|}\n\nPalastra was married to the former Anne Rich. They have a son and four daughters. He died in 2015 in [[Highlandville, Missouri]] where he lived.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ranger.org/page-577054/3257536|title=US Army Ranger Association, Inc. \u2013 GEN (Ret) Joseph T. Palastra Jr. \u2013 RHOF 2010 \u2013 dies in Highlandville, Missouri|work=ranger.org|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150407030049/http://www.ranger.org/page-577054/3257536|archivedate=2015-04-07}}</ref><ref name=obit/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{USGovernment|sourceURL=[http://ahecwebdds.carlisle.army.mil/awapps/main.jsp?flag=browse&smd=1&awdid=41]}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Palatra, Joseph T.}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:United States Army generals]]\n[[Category:United States Military Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:American Senior Army Aviators]]\n[[Category:Auburn University alumni]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of the Vietnam War]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Service Medal (US Army)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Silver Star]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Merit]]\n[[Category:People from Portsmouth, New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Air Medal]]\n[[Category:United States Army Command and General Staff College alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Defense Distinguished Service Medal]]\n[[Category:People from Kittery, Maine]]\n[[Category:People from Christian County, Missouri]]\n[[Category:Air War College alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= Joseph T. Palastra Jr.\n|image= Joseph Thomas Palastra JR.jpg\n|image_size= \n|alt= \n|caption= General Joseph T. Palastra Jr.\n|nickname= \n|birth_date= {{birth date|1931|11|10}}\n|birth_place= [[Kittery, Maine]]<ref name=obit>{{cite web|url=http://www.adamsfuneralhome.net/obituaries/Gen-Joseph-Palastra/#!/Obituary|title=Gen. Joseph Thomas Palastra Jr.|work=Gen. Joseph Thomas Palastra Jr. Obituary}}</ref>\n|death_date= {{death date and age|2015|03|03|1931|11|10}} \n|death_place= [[Highlandville, Missouri|Highlandville]], Missouri\n|allegiance= United States\n|branch= [[United States Army]]\n|serviceyears= 1954&ndash;1989\n|rank= [[General (United States)|General]]\n|servicenumber= \n|unit= \n|commands= [[United States Army Forces Command]]<br/>[[I Corps (United States)|I Corps]]<br/>[[5th Infantry Division (United States)|5th Infantry Division (Mechanized)]]<br/>3rd Brigade, [[101st Airborne Division]]<br/>[[12th Infantry Regiment (United States)|1st Battalion, 12th Infantry Regiment]]\n|battles= [[Vietnam War]]\n|awards= [[Defense Distinguished Service Medal]] (2)<br/>[[Army Distinguished Service Medal]]<br/>[[Silver Star]]<br/>[[Legion of Merit]]<br/>[[Bronze Star Medal]] (3)\n|relations= \n|laterwork= \n}}\n'''Joseph Thomas Palastra Jr.''' (November 10, 1931 \u2013 March 3, 2015) was a [[United States Army]] four-star general who served as Commanding General, [[United States Army Forces Command]] from 1986 to 1989. During his tenure, in 1987, the title was changed to Commander in Chief, Forces Command. He was inducted into the Ranger Hall of Fame, class of 2010.\n\n==Military career==\nA native of [[New Hampshire]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NVFAAQAAIAAJ&q=Palastra,+Joseph+T+1931&dq=Palastra,+Joseph+T+1931&hl=en&ei=aqKPTYK9HsSC0QHxuqycCw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAQ|title=Supplement to Who's who in America|work=google.com}}</ref> Palastra began his career as a second lieutenant after graduating from the [[United States Military Academy]] in 1954. Palastra also holds a Master of Business Administration from [[Auburn University]]. His military education includes the Infantry Officer Basic and Advanced Courses, the United States Army [[Command and General Staff College]] and the [[Air War College]].\n\nPalastra commanded [[I Corps (United States)|I Corps]] and [[Fort Lewis]], Washington. His other key assignments include Commanding General, [[5th Infantry Division (United States)|5th Infantry Division (Mechanized)]] and [[Fort Polk]], Louisiana; Chief of Staff, [[Eighth United States Army]]/[[United States Forces Korea]]; and Deputy Commander in Chief/Chief of Staff, [[United States Pacific Command]], [[Camp H.M. Smith]], Hawaii.\n\nIn 1968 and 1969 Palastra served in Vietnam as Commander, B Company, 4th Aviation Battalion, and as Commander, [[12th Infantry Regiment (United States)|1st Battalion, 12th Infantry Regiment]], in Vietnam's highlands. Palastra was a war-plans staff officer in the Office of the Deputy Chief of Staff for Military Operations, Washington, D.C., and, after attending the [[Air War College]], returned to Washington to serve as a force structure analyst in the Office of the Chief of Staff.\n\nPalastra has also commanded the 3rd Brigade of the [[101st Airborne Division]] at [[Fort Campbell]], Kentucky, and served as Deputy Director for Estimates in the [[Defense Intelligence Agency]].\n\n==Awards and decorations==\n{|\n|[[File:Combat Infantry Badge.svg|125px]]\n|[[Combat Infantryman Badge]]\n|-\n|[[File:Army Senior Aviator.png|120px]]\n|[[United States Aviator Badge|Army Senior Aviator Badge]]\n|-\n|[[File:Ranger Tab.svg|80px]]\n|[[Ranger tab]]\n|-\n|[[File:USAFSeniorParatrooper.jpg|80px]]\n|[[Parachutist Badge (United States)|Senior Parachutist Badge]]\n|-\n|[[File:Office of the Secretary of Defense Identification Badge.png|80px]]\n|[[Office of the Secretary of Defense Identification Badge]]\n|-\n|[[File:United States Army Staff Identification Badge.png|80px]]\n|[[Army Staff Identification Badge]]\n|}\n{|\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=oak|name=Defense Distinguished Service ribbon|width=60}}\n|[[Defense Distinguished Service Medal]] with one bronze [[oak leaf cluster]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Distinguished Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Army Distinguished Service Medal]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Silver Star BAR.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Silver Star]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Legion of Merit ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Legion of Merit]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Bronze Star ribbon.svg|width=60}}<span style=\"position:relative; top: 0px; left: -48px; display: inline-block; width: 0;\">[[File:\"V\" device, brass.svg|12px]]</span><span style=\"position:relative; top: 0px; left: -36px; display: inline-block; width: 0;\">[[File:Bronze oakleaf-3d.svg|14px]]</span><span style=\"position:relative; top: 0px; left: -24px; display: inline-block; width: 0;\">[[File:Bronze oakleaf-3d.svg|14px]]</span>\n|[[Bronze Star]] with [[\"V\" device]] and two oak leaf clusters\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=oak|ribbon=Meritorious Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Meritorious Service Medal (United States)|Meritorious Service Medal]] with oak leaf cluster\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=Air Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}<span style=\"position:relative; top: 0px; left: -36px; display: inline-block; width: 0;\">[[File:Award numeral 8.png|12px]]</span>\n|[[Air Medal]] with bronze [[award numeral]] 8\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=United States Army and U.S. Air Force Presidential Unit Citation ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Presidential Unit Citation (United States)|Army Presidential Unit Citation]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=National Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[National Defense Service Medal]] with one bronze [[service star]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Armed Forces Expeditionary Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}<span style=\"position:relative; top: 0px; left: -41px; display: inline-block; width: 0;\">[[File:Bronze-service-star-3d.png|11px]]</span><span style=\"position:relative; top: 0px; left: -30px; display: inline-block; width: 0;\">[[File:Bronze-service-star-3d.png|11px]]</span>\n|[[Armed Forces Expeditionary Medal]] with one service star\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Army Service Ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Army Service Ribbon]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=numeral|ribbon=Army Overseas Service Ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Overseas Service Ribbon#Army|Army Overseas Service Ribbon]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=Vietnamese Gallantry Cross ribbon.svg|width=60}}<span style=\"position:relative; top: 0px; left: -37px; display: inline-block; width: 0;\">[[File:Bronze-service-star-3d.png|15px]]</span>\n|[[Vietnam Gallantry Cross]] with bronze star\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=|type=|ribbon=Vietnam Campaign Medal ribbon with 60- clasp.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Vietnam Campaign Medal]]\n|}\n\nPalastra was married to the former Anne Rich. They have a son and four daughters. He died in 2015 in [[Highlandville, Missouri]] where he lived.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ranger.org/page-577054/3257536|title=US Army Ranger Association, Inc. - GEN (Ret) Joseph T. Palastra Jr. -- RHOF 2010 -- dies in Highlandville, Missouri|work=ranger.org|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150407030049/http://www.ranger.org/page-577054/3257536|archivedate=2015-04-07}}</ref><ref name=obit/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{USGovernment|sourceURL=[http://ahecwebdds.carlisle.army.mil/awapps/main.jsp?flag=browse&smd=1&awdid=41]}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Palatra, Joseph T.}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:United States Army generals]]\n[[Category:United States Military Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:American Senior Army Aviators]]\n[[Category:Auburn University alumni]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of the Vietnam War]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Service Medal (US Army)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Silver Star]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Merit]]\n[[Category:People from Portsmouth, New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Air Medal]]\n[[Category:United States Army Command and General Staff College alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Defense Distinguished Service Medal]]\n[[Category:People from Kittery, Maine]]\n[[Category:People from Christian County, Missouri]]\n[[Category:Air War College alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Abraham, B.S.", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_T._Palastra_Jr."}
{"title_page": "Dizzee Rascal discography", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox artist discography\n| Artist          = [[Dizzee Rascal]]\n| Image           = Dizzee Rascal - Ilosaarirock 2009 2.jpg\n| Caption         = Dizzee Rascal performing at the 2009 [[Ilosaarirock]] in [[Joensuu]], Finland\n| Studio          = 6\n| EP              = 1\n| Live            = 1 \n| Music videos    = \n| Singles         = 32\n| Option          = 2\n| Option name     = Mixtapes\n}}\n\nEnglish rapper [[Dizzee Rascal]] has released six [[studio album]]s, one [[live album]], one [[extended play]], 32 [[single (music)|singles]] (including nine singles as a featured artist), two [[charity record|charity releases]], two [[promotional single]]s and two [[mixtape]]s.\n\nDizzee Rascal released his debut [[studio album]], ''[[Boy in da Corner]]'', on 21 July 2003, in the [[United Kingdom]], where it peaked at number twenty-three; having been certified as gold by the [[British Phonographic Industry]] (BPI). The album was preceded by the rapper's debut single, \"[[I Luv U (Dizzee Rascal song)|I Luv U]]\", which peaked at number twenty-nine on the [[UK Singles Chart]]. The singles \"[[Fix Up, Look Sharp]]\" and \"[[Jus' a Rascal]]\" were also released from the album in 2003, reaching peaks of number seventeen and thirty, respectively, in the UK. The rapper's second studio album, ''[[Showtime (Dizzee Rascal album)|Showtime]]'' was released on 6 September 2004, where it debuted at number eight in the UK and number sixty-five in [[Ireland]]. The album's [[lead single]], \"[[Stand Up Tall]]\" was released on 23 August 2004, marking Dizzee Rascal's first top-ten single when it peaked at number ten. The album also saw the release of \"[[Dream (Dizzee Rascal song)|Dream]]\" and the double A-side \"[[Off 2 Work]]\"/\"[[Graftin']]\", which reached peaks of number fourteen and number forty-four in the UK, respectively.\n\nA third studio album, ''[[Maths + English]]'', was released on 4 June 2007, where it debuted at number seven in the UK and number fifty-seven in Ireland. The album saw the release of three singles, \"[[Sirens (Dizzee Rascal song)|Sirens]]\", \"[[Pussyole (Old Skool)]]\" and \"[[Flex (song)|Flex]]\", which reached peaks of number twenty, twenty-two and twenty-three, respectively, in the UK. On 22 June 2008, Dizzee Rascal released \"[[Dance wiv Me]]\", a collaboration with singer Chrome and songwriter/producer [[Calvin Harris]]. The track saw commercial success for the rapper when it debuted at number-one in the UK, also reaching number five in Ireland and number thirteen in [[Australia]]. The single spent four consecutive weeks at the top of the UK chart and was certified platinum the following year for surpassing sales of 600,000 copies. The rapper continued the line of success when follow-up singles \"[[Bonkers (song)|Bonkers]]\", produced by [[Armand van Helden]], and \"[[Holiday (Dizzee Rascal song)|Holiday]]\", featuring Chrome, both topped the UK chart. The fourth studio album, ''[[Tongue N' Cheek]]'', was released on 21 September 2009, peaking at number three in the UK and number twenty in Ireland. It was succeeded by the release of a fourth single, \"[[Dirtee Cash]]\", which gave the rapper a fourth consecutive top-ten hit when it peaked at number ten.\n\nAt the [[2010 BRIT Awards]], Dizzee collaborated with [[British people|British]] indie rock band [[Florence and the Machine]], performing \"[[You Got the Love#You Got the Dirtee Love|You Got the Dirtee Love]]\", a mash-up of \"[[You Got the Love#Florence and the Machine version|You've Got the Love]]\" and \"Dirtee Cash\". The collaboration was then released as a [[music download|digital download]], peaking at number two in the United Kingdom and number twenty-four in Ireland. The album, ''Tongue N' Cheek'', was re-issued in June 2010 to include the collaboration and celebrate the platinum certification of the album itself. The 'Dirtee Deluxe' edition of the album included the single \"[[Dirtee Disco]]\", which gave the rapper a fourth solo number-one single when it topped the chart in May 2010.\n\nThe rapper returned to the charts in 2012 following the release of \"[[Scream (Dizzee Rascal song)|Scream]]\", which featured ''[[Must Be the Music (TV series)|Must Be the Music]]'' finalist Pepper (of Pepper & Piano). It became the artist's nineteenth top forty hit in the United Kingdom when it debuted at number twenty-two in August 2012.\n\nDizzee Rascal has also appeared as a featured artist on several occasions, the first of which was \"[[Lucky Star (Basement Jaxx song)|Lucky Star]]\" (2003), a collaboration with [[Basement Jaxx]] that peaked at number twenty-three in the UK. The rapper has also collaborated with [[The Brighton Port Authority]] on the track \"[[Toe Jam (The Brighton Port Authority song)|Toe Jam]]\" (2008) and with [[Newham Generals|D Double E]] on the track \"Bluku! Bluku!\" (2011). Most notably is Dizzee Rascal's collaboration with Colombian singer [[Shakira]], \"[[Loca (Shakira song)|Loca]]\". The track proved an international hit, topping charts worldwide, including [[Poland]], [[Portugal]] and [[Spain]]; also peaking at number thirty-two on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. In 2010, the rapper collaborated with British producer [[DJ Fresh]] on the track \"[[The Power (DJ Fresh song)|The Power]]\"&mdash;which peaked at number six in the United Kingdom. The rapper has also been involved in two charity releases: firstly as [[Band Aid 20]] in 2004 on the track \"[[Do They Know It's Christmas?|Do They Know It's Christmas]]\" and secondly as part of [[Shout for England]] in 2010 on the track \"[[Shout (Shout for England song)|Shout]]\" with [[James Corden]], both peaking at number one in the UK and Ireland.\n\n==Albums==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n|+ List of studio albums, with selected